<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Loss-Making Enterprises Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The number of Vietnamese
state-owned enterprises operating at a loss increased from 22
percent in 1996 to more than 30 percent in 1997, the Vietnam News
Agency (VNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Lack of regulations in management and supervision was the main
reason, the report quoted experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
There are now more than 6,000 enterprises throughout nation run
by the state, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
