<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Truckers to Sue France over Blockades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 19 (Xinhua) -- German trucking companies said
Monday in Frankfurt they would sue French authorities in French
courts for losses caused by French strikers' blockades last
November.
</P>
<P>
The companies said their trans-European freight was delayed
because of the French strikers' barricades, resulting in losses
estimated at around 20 million marks (11 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, their claims based on bills of lading and tachometer
readings from the detained trucks had been rejected by most French
regional administrations. They said the documentation was
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
The tachometer is a sealed device carried by all trucks in the
European Union which details time, speed and distance of travel.
</P>
<P>
The French strike last year caused about 50 million dollars' in
losses to German truck companies. Some claims from the companies
have not yet been settled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
