<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Martin Luther King Jr. Day Marked in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Three decades after the
murder of American civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr.,
the nation is honoring him with prayers and marches across the
country.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore planned to visit Monday the Atlanta
church where King once preached. Gore reportedly will announce a
civil rights initiative to be presented to Congress.
</P>
<P>
The proposal would raise civil rights spending in the 1999
budget, according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
The proposal would strengthen enforcement of fair-housing laws,
investigation of police brutality and enforcement of the Americans
With Disabilities Act. Money would be spent to ease the caseload
at the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission by placing greater
emphasis on mediators to settle job discrimination complaints.
</P>
<P>
King is to be honored at dozens of ceremonies across the
country, who was assassinated in Memphis, Tennessee, on April 4,
1968. He was 39.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
