<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Supreme Court Discusses Recommendations by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The recommendation made by
Prime Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa of Nepal to dissolve the
parliament and hold mid-term polls gained the upper hand on the
first day of the discussions held Monday by the Supreme Court on
the opinion it is to present to King Birendra, the official RSS
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The RSS said Attorney General Prem Bahadur Bista argued that
the recommendation by Prime Minister Thapa is in accordance with
the constitution and has already been activated, therefore it
should be given the preference.
</P>
<P>
He said the submission to call a special session of the
parliament should not have been made on the basis of mere
assumptions that the government is on the verge of losing its
majority, adding that the prime minister commanded a majority of
107 MPs on his side at the time.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Thapa made the recommendation to King Birendra
on January 8 after learning that the main opposition Communist
Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) had planned a
no-confidence motion against his coalition government.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the CPN-UML and nine MPs from Thapa's own
National Democratic Party (RPP) asked the King to convene a
special session of the parliament to discuss their no-confidence
motion against the government.
</P>
<P>
After days of consultations with advisors, legal experts and
party leaders, King Birendra could not make a decision, so he
referred the matter to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The court had handed down conflicting verdicts over prime
ministers' recommendations to dissolve parliament and hold fresh
polls. In 1994, it ruled that Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala
of the Nepali Congress (NC) was within his constitutional
authority to make such a recommendation.
</P>
<P>
But the following year, it overturned the similar
recommendation made to the King by Prime Minister Man Mohan
Adhikari of the CPN-UML, ruling that dissolution was not allowed
if an alternative government could be formed from the existing
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The ruling NC's representative argued during Monday's
discussions that the prime minister recommended the dissolution of
the parliament well before the submission seeking a special
session, so the prime minister's recommendation should take
precedence.
</P>
<P>
Senior Prosecutor Balaram K.C. supported the NC's stand.
</P>
<P>
Laxman Lal Karna, representative of the ruling Nepal Sadbhavana
Party, argued that Article 53 (4) has provided for the dissolution
of parliament as a privilege of the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He said there is no possibility of forming a stable alternative
government under the present circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Thapa's is the fourth government since the mid-term polls in
late 1994. He came to power on October 7, 1997 after the NC
brought down the former coalition government with a no-confidence
motion.
</P>
<P>
The discussions are expected to last days before the Supreme
Court can come up with an opinion for King Birendra.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
