<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1545 GMT, January 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Chief arms inspector of the U.N. Richard Butler
arrived here Monday afternoon on a three-day visit to Iraq in a
bid to solve the current crisis over arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
Butler, chairman of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, will hold talks
with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz on the question of
arm inspectors' access to Iraqi presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
Butler paid his last visit to Baghdad five weeks ago, during
which he failed to persuade Iraq into agreeing to grant access to
arms inspectors to presidential sites, which Iraq views as symbols
of national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council issued a presidential statement
after Butler reported results of his Baghdad visit, asking Iraq
to allow arms inspectors to go any where, at any time immediately
and without conditions.
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- A group of armed "Interahamwe" militiamen Monday
ambushed a bus carrying workers of the Rwanda Breweries Company in
Gisenyi, north-western Rwanda, killing 35 people and wounding 35
others, reported the Rwanda News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"The massacre occurred as the bus transporting the employees
from the town was stopped by a small group of armed criminals,"
officials in Gisenyi said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five bodies were killed on the spot, while 10 of the 35
seriously wounded died at Gisenyi Hospital where they have been
taken to for treatment.
</P>
<P>
The death toll is expected to rise as many more workers who
jumped out of the bus remain unaccounted for, the officials
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said
Monday that his government would consider the International
Monetary Fund (IMF)'s suggestion on raising local interest rates.
</P>
<P>
"I think the IMF is a responsible international body which does
not threaten... it is giving advice to us," Mahathir told
reporters after chairing the 4th Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC)
Implementation Council Meeting at Cyberjaya near here.
</P>
<P>
The suggestion came from IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus
 after he wrapped up initial consultations with Malaysian Deputy
Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim as well as
Malaysian Treasury and State Bank officials here last week.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates in Malaysia are currently hovering at around 9.5
 percent from an average of 7.5 percent before the attacks on
regional currencies last July, while the local currency of ringgit
 which fell to a low of 4.88 against the U.S. dollar two weeks
ago, has recovered to a high of 4.05 level in intra-day trading
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
