<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Delegation Visits France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of the United States
Congress, headed by House of Representatives Foreign Committee
Chairman Benjamin Gilman, is paying a two-day visit to France from
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The delegation members discussed with French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine a series of issues from U.S. extra-territorial laws
to Franco-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said
that the visit by the U.S. Congressmen, the first in several
years, is of "particular importance" for France.
</P>
<P>
Besides Gilman, the delegation consists of six other House
Representatives, both Republican and Democrat. They will meet
President Jacques Chirac, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and Defense
Minister Alain Richard on Tuesday before leaving for Poland.
</P>
<P>
"We are in fact paying great importance to developing our
relations with the Congress of the United States which plays a
considerable role in the American foreign policy," said the
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted diplomatic sources as saying
that Vedrine talked with the delegation the peace process in the
Middle East, Bosnia, Cuba, Iran, Iraq as well as the
extra-territorial laws passed by the U.S. Congress such as the
Helms-Burton and D'Amato laws which ban foreign companies from
doing business in Cuba and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine stressed the "complementarity" rather than
confrontation between the European Union and the United States
over all these issues, said AFP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
