<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demonstrations in Harare Turns Violent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Shops in and around Harare,
capital of Zimbabwe were looted today by people who were
demonstrating against recent price hikes of commodities.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Mabvuku left a trail of destruction at
Tsokachena, the biggest shopping center in the area, as people
stoned shops and looted mostly essential goods such as
mealie-meal, sugar and cooking oil.
</P>
<P>
The residents also broke into shops such as Bata Shoe Company,
a retail shop, Powersales and a Marowa bottle store.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the looters were youths and women, some with
babies strapped on their backs.
</P>
<P>
In Chitungwiza, demonstrators picketed around Makoni Shopping
Center after dismantling an Aroma Bakeries truck, a marketing car
and a Lobels truck, leaving a trail of destruction as they tried
to loot.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators chanted anti-white and anti-government
slogans.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations were triggered by the recent 20 percent
price hike of commodities due to the devaluation of the
Zimbabwean Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The government said today that it had reversed the move by
millers to increase the prices of mealie-meal by 21 percent and
would review prices of all commodities.
</P>
<P>
"The government no longer controls prices. Prices are now set
by producers of each commodities," said Nathan Shamuyarira,
Minister of Industry and Commerce Minister. However, he added
that the government has looked into proposed increases by
millers.
</P>
<P>
Millers had planned to increase the price of mealie-meal by 21
percent with effect from today, citing the drying up of maize
sources. This is the third hike within two and a half months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
