<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt Blamed for Goods' Price Hikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's opposition United
Parties (UP) today said the recent price hikes on almost all
basic commodities should not be blamed on the whites, but also on
the gross mismanagement of the country's macro-economic policies.
</P>
<P>
UP's Information Secretary General Isaac Manyemba said heavy
taxation and high interest rates were forcing business
entrepreneurs to increase prices of their goods and services so
as to remain in business.
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to the fact that the recent price increments were
being caused by whites trying to sabotage the economy, there are
other factors. This is emanating from the gross macro-economic
mismanagement of policies by the government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prices on basic commodities were raised early this month by
over 20 percent with producers citing the rise on the devaluation
of the country's currency.
</P>
<P>
Harare South member of parliament Margaret Dongo said the
government must accept responsibility for the strike and damages
incurred during the demonstrations which turned violent in most
high density suburbs. Shops in the central business district
were forced to close today.
</P>
<P>
"The mismanagement of the economy by the government has
resulted in all this. Where did they think things will go?" she
asked.
</P>
<P>
Ropafadzo Benjamin, coordinator of the National Association of
Social Workers, implored the Ministry of Industry and Commerce,
the private sector and other stake-holders to find a solution to
the price increases through dialogue now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
