<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namiba's Oldest English Newspaper Shuts Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Windhoek Advertizer,
Namibia's oldest English-language newspaper, closed down today
after its sustained financial difficulties and staff shortage,
South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The 79-year-old newspaper, run by the Democratic Media
Holdings (DMH) group, was last year turned into Nambia's first
afternoon daily in an effort to rescue it from financial
problems.
</P>
<P>
The paper was reportedly running at about 200,000 U.S.
Dollars' loss. Besides, three journalists recently resigned from
the newspaper, leaving it with only three full-time news
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Following the close-down of the newspaper, its staff members
will be integrated into the Afrikaans daily Die Repbulikein, and
will publish an English insert for the paper.
</P>
<P>
Windhoek Advertizer appeared for the first time on July 4,
1919, and was originally a news sheet for members of the United
Club -- a social club for Union of South African Servicemen
stationed in Namibia after the Germans surrendered in 1915.
</P>
<P>
It was then bought by Windhoek businessman Johan Meinert. In
the 1970s, the paper was run by well-known Namibian newsman
Hannes Smit, now editor-in-chief for the Observer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
