<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some 7,000 Remain Powerless in Maine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Some 70,000 people are still
without power in the northeastern state of Maine 12 days after the
massive ice storm that struck several U.S. states and a large area
of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The January 8 storm left hundreds of thousands of residents,
including 250,000 in Maine, without power.
</P>
<P>
Despite utility workers from the state with federal assistance
have been busying with the restoration of electricity, continued
snow storms in the last few days dragged the pace.
</P>
<P>
Several hundreds of crews of Maine's largest utility, Central
Maine Power, were continuing to hook up the remaining 30,000 homes
and businesses still off line, the United Press International said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
State officials said there were still 330 people staying in
shelters overnight Sunday and 37 shelters remained open Monday.
</P>
<P>
Local officials estimate that the damage by the storm was up to
100 million U.S. dollars in the Maine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
