<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks' Merger Dominates Big M&AMP;A in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Commercial banks' merger
activities have dominated big deals of U.S. mergers and
acquisitions (M&AMP;A) in the last five years, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,492 mergers worth over 200 billion U.S. dollars
took place in U.S. commercial banks, standing in the first line of
big M&AMP;A deals, the Securities Data Company (SDC) reported.
</P>
<P>
Radio and television have accounted for the second biggest M&AMP;A
with 1,435 deals worth 162 billion dollars, the SDC was quoted by
the New York Times today.
</P>
<P>
Other big deals in M&AMP;A include the insurance industry with
5,114 deals worth 110 billion dollars completed; health services
worth 107 billion dollars; investment brokers, 104 billion
dollars; utilities, 100 billion dollars; oil and gas refining, 96
billion dollars and hotel and casinos, 84 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the United States saw not only the record amount of
M&AMP;A totaling 1 trillion dollars, but also the unprecedented number
of big M&AMP;As.
</P>
<P>
There were 156 mergers of 1 billion dollars or more, 60 percent
higher than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The economic turmoil in Asia has not halted the M&AMP;A drive of
many U.S. firms.
</P>
<P>
In the first two weeks of 1998, there were reports of AT&AMP;T's of
11.3 billion dollars to acquire Teleport Communications Group and
SBC Communications' offer of 4.4 billion dollars to buy Southern
New England Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The M&AMP;A drive has gained momentum as a result of a change in
the strategy of companies from downsizing themselves to trying to
be bigger as key to profitability when globalization became a
trend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
