<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar Urged to Stop Prejudice Against Egyptian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today called on Qatar to stop all measures against
Egyptians working in the small rich Arab emirate, the Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He issued the call in the wake of the Qatari Interior
Ministry's decision to lay off large numbers of Egyptian
expatriates. About 160 Egyptians have been fired after tensions
mounted between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Egyptian diplomats in the Qatari capital of Doha,
the rest of the 5,000 Egyptians working in Qatar's public sector
can expect their dismissal by summer if relations between the two
countries do not improve.
</P>
<P>
Hiring Egyptian workers in Qatar has been banned since November
1996, according to the MENA.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that "it is inappropriate that such
measures are adopted against the Egyptians who carry out their
duties in full in Qatar."
</P>
<P>
He termed these measures as "unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Tensions heightened as the two sides quarreled over alleged
Egyptian involvement in a failed coup in Qatar in February 1996,
and Egypt's opposition to a regional economic conference in Doha
in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
The war of words led to the suspension of a meeting of the
eight-member Damascus Declaration states scheduled in Doha on
December 1-2, 1997, to which they belong.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia's mediation in December between Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak and Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani
failed to produce concrete results.
</P>
<P>
About 25,000 Egyptians are living in Qatar, whose foreign labor
accounts for two thirds of the countrys' entire residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
