<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Reports on Progress of Identification for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Great progress has been
made in the identification for participation in the referendum to
decide the future of the Western Sahara, but a lot remained
undone, UN Secretary-General said today.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report to the Security Council, Annan said
between August 1994, when the identification process was launched,
and December 1995, when it came to a standstill, a total of 77,058
persons had been convoked, of whom 60,112 had been identified.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said between December 3, 1997 and January
10, 1998, a total of 18,688 persons were convoked, and 13,227
identified.
</P>
<P>
Annan noted the completion of the identification phase by May
31, 1998 will be a daunting and arduous task since there are still
100,000 applicants remaining to be convoked and identified in less
than five months.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said in conformity with the Houston agreement, he
had decided to instruct the United Nations Mission for the
Referendum in Western Sahara (MINURSO) to proceed as soon as
possible with the identification of those unconvoked individuals
who represented themselves on the days of convocation of their
respective tribal groups.
</P>
<P>
Annan said with regard to applicants from non-contested tribes
resident in northern Morocco, who were initially expected to
travel to the identification centers in southern Morocco, he has
concluded to convoke and identify them in the northern part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General urged Morocco and the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Saguia el-Hamra and Rio de oro(POLISARIO) to
ensure that the identification proceed smoothly. He also urged the
two sides to keep the momentum so as to start the transitional
period in June 1998 as planned.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the security Council of the United Nations and
the General Assembly to extend all necessary support in this
regard, so that the overall objective of holding the referendum by
the end of 1998 may still be maintained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
