<HEADLINE> Iraq Urged to Comply with UN Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 19 (Xinhua) -- U.N. chief arms inspector
Richard Butler said here Monday that Iraq should comply with the
decisions of the Security Council with respect to U.N. arms
inspectors' access to Iraq's presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
Butler, chairman of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, told a news
conference that he hoped that the two sides can come to terms with
respect to the issue of access.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the Security Council has asked him to find
ways to respect Iraq's sovereignty, dignity and national security.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that this should not be against the principle
of ensuring inspectors' complete access.
</P>
<P>
Butler said he would hold talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz Monday evening and Tuesday, and he would end
his visit on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said he will be discussing with Aziz the issues of access,
and the UNSCOM' s continuing monitoring and inspection work in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
When asked how he thinks of the deadline that Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein set for the inspectors to end their work, Butler
said he has to know more about what is intended in Saddam's speech.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that as long as Iraq is fully cooperative,
the inspection work can be very quick.
</P>
<P>
Saddam said in his address marking the seventh anniversary of
the Gulf War last Saturday that Iraq would stop its cooperation
with UNSCOM unless the Security Council honors its promise that it
will lift the sanctions imposed on Iraq after it has destroyed all
its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi president reiterated the deadline which the Iraqi
National Assembly had set for arms inspectors to end their work
within six months.
</P>
<P>
Butler said Russian, French, Chinese and Canadian
Representatives in the UNSCOM would attend the talks between him
and Aziz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
