<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-19 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Redeployment No More Than 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 19 (Xinhua) -- As Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu heading for Washington for talks with U.S.
President Bill Clinton, an Israeli minister said Monday the
percentage of second troop redeployment would not exceed 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications Minister Limor Livnat told Israel Radio that
the cabinet would never accept a double-digit redeployment in the
West Bank. She was commenting on the pending talks between
Netanyahu and Clinton, during which the Israeli redeployment will
be a top issue.
</P>
<P>
"What I can say is that we are not talking about two-digit,
definitely not. And I believe this is the majority (view) of the
cabinet. This government will not take any decision of more than
one digit, or more than 10 percent," she said.
</P>
<P>
Livnat, a hawkish cabinet member, said the cabinet is waiting
to see the results of the Netanyahu-Clinton meeting and the
fulfillment of commitments by the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA). She said Israel would not bow to any outside pressure, even
from Washington, to make compromise on territorial issues.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is reportedly trying to persuade Israel to redeploy
from 12-15 percent of the West Bank in the second of three-phase
redeployments.
</P>
<P>
Livnat made it clear that Israel would not take any dictations
from anybody including the U.S.. "I believe it's in the American
interests to have a safe Israel, to have a strong Israel, and to
let us to take the decision about our future, about our existence
by ourselves," she added.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, leading moderate within the
cabinet, expressed the hope that during the talks Clinton would
hold with Netanyahu and PNA leader Yasser Arafat, a principle
would be found on how to continue the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the ceremony held at the Hatzerim Air
Force Base in southern Israel for the arrival of two F-15I fighter
planes from the U.S., Mordechai said Israel is urging the PNA to
fulfill its commitments to the signed agreements before deciding
to implement the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Israeli opposition leaders have publicly lowered their
expectations for the Washington talks. Former Prime Minister
Shimon Peres, one of the leading architects of the peace process,
said Clinton would do no more than just trying to persuade
Netanyahu and Arafat to soften their positions.
</P>
<P>
Peres expressed the belief that Clinton would not go so far as
to issue an ultimatum to both sides to push forward the peace
process. He noted that Netanyahu's manoeuvring room was limited
by the hardliners who dominate his coalition.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Meretz Party's leader Yossi Sarid, meanwhile,
called on Clinton to support the establishment of an independent
and sovereign Palestinian state. He said this was the new fact of
political life in the region, and will be the basis for fruitful
negotiations between Israel and the PNA.
</P>
<P>
But Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky dismissed
Sarid's remarks as "ridiculous." He blasted Sarid for trying to
create new realities in the peace process, saying "this is not
the way to help the peace process in general, and the
Israeli people in particular." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
