<HEADLINE> Nigeria-Japan Trade Records Continuous Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Bilateral trade between Nigeria
and Japan has witnessed continuous growth in the last few years,
the News Agency of Nigeria reported today, quoting figures from
the Japanese External Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, the trade volume between the two
countries increased to 317.9 million U.S. Dollars in the first
nine months of 1997 from 275 million Dollars compared with the
same period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Total trade volume for 1996 stood at 476 million Dollars,
compared with 313.8 million Dollars in 1995, the official agency
said.
</P>
<P>
The data also show that Japan has maintained trade balance
advantage in the three years under review.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Japan exported 179.1 million Dollars worth of exports
to Nigeria and imported goods valued at 134.7 million Dollars.
The two figures expanded to 310 million Dollars and 166.5 million
Dollars in 1996 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The trend was the same in the January-September period of last
year, when Nigeria exported goods valued at 154.4 million Dollars
and imported 163.5 million Dollars worth of products.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil accounted for 141.9 million Dollars of the Nigeria's
total exports to Japan in the nine months under review, while the
share of sesame seeds came to 10.1 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iron and steel, buses, trucks, passenger cars and engines were
the five biggest commodities of the Japanese exports to Nigeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
