<HEADLINE> Butler to Start Talks in Baghdad: U.N. Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Chief U.N. weapons
inspector Richard Butler left his hotel in Baghdad "moments ago" to
start his talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz, U.N.
Spokesman Fred Eckhard said at the noon briefing here today.
</P>
<P>
The main item of Butler's agenda remains the question of access
to all sites by UNSCOM, Butler's U.N. Special Commission, charged
with dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, he said.
</P>
<P>
Butler also indicated that he wants to seek a clarification from
Aziz on Iraq's statement issued over the weekend that it intends
to set a deadline for the work of UNSCOM unless the U.N. sanctions
against Iraq are lifted, Eckhard added.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein was reported to have said on
Saturday that he might implement a six-month deadline set by Iraq's
parliament for the inspectors to complete their work.
</P>
<P>
Butler has rejected the deadline on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-Iraqi dispute flared again last week when Iraq barred
an inspection team led by American Scott Ritter from operating,
accusing him of spying for the United States.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council in a statement called again for
unstricted access to inspectors. 
