<HEADLINE> Georgia Favors Peaceful Settlement of Abkazian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The leadership of Georgia stands
for a peaceful settlement of confrontation with the breakaway
region of Abkhazia, Georgian president Eduard Shevardnadze said on
Monday, according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with national radio Shevardnadze said "for this
reason we have been continuing the negotiation process" which has
already lasted for more than four years, although it so far has
yielded no positive results.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze noted that Georgia is against resumption of the
war on Abkhazia and "if somebody calls for the war, he must bear
responsibility for it."
</P>
<P>
He calls on the conflicting sides not to be carried away by
emotion and continue the search for peaceful solutions.
</P>
<P>
On the Russian peacekeepers in the area the president
reaffirmed that the Russian troops should leave unless they
protect the return of Georgian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze on January 2 told reporters that his country would
not refuse to use so-called "Bosnian format" and compulsion
elements to settle the Abkhazian conflict, if there are no real
steps to return refugee home and restore the territorial integrity
of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze today also expressed hope that the international
community will support such a proposal in which this question is
raised. 
</P>
