<HEADLINE> Iran, Iraq to Form Committees to Settle Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Iraq have agreed to
form two committees to solve their disputes to pave the way for
their rapprochement, the Iranian official news agency IRNA
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during talks between Iranian Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharrazi and his Iraqi counterpart Mohammed Saeed
al-Sahhaf, who arrived here last Friday on his first official
visit, the IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
One of the committees is for settling the issue of prisoners of
war and those missing in action, which is left over by the war
from 1980 to 1988 between the two neighbors, according to the IRNA.
</P>
<P>
It will also take up other humanitarian issues.
</P>
<P>
Iran says it has released 49,196 Iraqi POWs and that some
15,000 Iranian POWs are still held in Iraq. But Iraq has rejected
the claim and accused Iran of holding some 18,000 Iraqi POWs.
</P>
<P>
The other committee is to deal with issues of commerce and
pilgrimage, with a mission to find ways of improving bilateral
commercial cooperation based on the United Nations resolutions on
Iraq and easing travels of people between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is considered as a constructive step to improve
the relations of the two former foes, since the issue of POWs is
the major hurdle for their rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
As a goodwill signal to Iran, the Iraqi government unilaterally
lifted the ban of Iranian citizens on paying pilgrimage to the
Shiite holy sites in Iraq last August.
</P>
<P>
During the eighth summit of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference held here last December, the two countries expressed
willingness to improve their relations and underlined the need to
resolve their disputes for future cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
