<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Claims Recapture of Diamond Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- There has been a stream of
claims and counter-claims since Sierra Leone's Kamajor militia
captured the diamond rich town of Tongofield in the east of the
country last weekend.
</P>
<P>
In the capital Freetown, the ruling military junta has
conceded the fall of the town but announced the recapture of it
by driving away the Kamajors, a group of hunter militiamen who
have been fighting to restore ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah
since the coup last May.
</P>
<P>
"This morning i got a telephone call from the Chief of Army
Staff that Tongo had been recaptured at about 10:00 a.m.
yesterday," said Aliu Kamara, spokesman with the junta, quoted by
the British Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
According to him, about 1,000 soldiers loyal to the junta were
put in the heavy fighting to retake the diamond production base,
a key source of government revenue.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 people were allegedly killed by the junta
forces.
</P>
<P>
But the Kamajor commander has denied to have the information
about the loss of Tongofield to the junta, saying that if it was
true, the civil defense unit would try to take it back again.
</P>
<P>
The fighting in the town has forced thousands of local people
to flee by roads to Kenema, the eastern capital about 20 km away,
according to relief agency officials.
</P>
<P>
Kenema residents said reportedly that lines of refugees were
trudging along the road, leaving their homes for refuge camps
organized by a number of international and local relief
agencies.
</P>
<P>
According to agency reports, the relief agencies are
coordinating their efforts to provide food, shelter and medicine
for the thousands who were pouring into the camps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
