<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets Foreign Policy Aides on Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 19 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Monday met with his foreign policy advisers, aimed at setting a
tone for the upcoming talks with Israeli and Palestinian leaders
over deadlocked preace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The 45-minute meeting included Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, National Security Adviser Sandy Berger, U.S. Middle East
envoy Dennis Ross and Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk,
White House spokesman Barry Toiv told reporters.
</P>
<P>
A Clinton administration official said the president intended
to remind Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Chairman of the Palestinian Authority Yasir Arafat "that they
are partners in the peace process" and must take each other's
need into account.
</P>
<P>
In her interview with NBC's "Meet the Press" on Sunday,
Albright emphasized that the United States would work hard to
"get the parties to come together and get the peace process back
on track."
</P>
<P>
She said President Clinton would make his views known during
his talks with Netanyahu and Arafat, but "ultimately the
decisions required have to come from the leaders."
</P>
<P>
Clinton will meet Netanyahu on Tuesday, and some analysts said
that during just one-hour meeting the U.S. president appears to be
lending a slightly frosty tone to the Israeli prime minister by
stripping it of the courtesies that typically mark summits between
U.S. and Israeli leaders.
</P>
<P>
"We don't think there's an unlimited amount of time here,"
Berger told CBS's "Face the Nation" program on Sunday. "There's
a sense of urgency that we have, and this is the time for tough
decisions."
</P>
<P>
The White House said last week that the talks will focus
merely on the Israeli-Palestinian peace process without covering
other regional issues.
</P>
<P>
It also will not offer the Israeli prime minister a lunch or
dinner with Clinton, nor will Netanyahu stay in the Blair House
official guest residence. And the two leaders will also not appear
side-by-side at a news conference after their talks.
</P>
<P>
"We believe this is the appropriate way to do this visit,"
Toiv said without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet on Sunday delayed any decision on how
much land to give up in the next West Bank withdrawal until
after Netanyahu's meeting with Clinton. The Israeli prime
minister told CNN that the size and pace of that withdrawal was
"something I plan to take up with the president (Clinton)."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
