<HEADLINE> French Judiciary Urged to Reconsider Garaudy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Head of Iranian judiciary
Mohammad Yazdi Monday called on the French judiciary to reconsider
the trial on French writer Roger Garaudy.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi said that the French judiciary should not be intimidated
by political hue and cry in defending justice, according to the
Iranian official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a group of Iranian judicial officials, Yazdi said
that by trying Garaudy, a French Muslim philosopher, the French
judiciary in fact put freedom on trial.
</P>
<P>
Garaudy, 84, is on trial for his book "Les Mythes Fondeteurs
de la Politique Israelienne" (Founding Myths of Israeli Politics)
published in 1996. He denied in the book the existence of gas
chambers for the extermination of Jews, saying that the
extermination of 6 million Jews during World War II by the
Nazis is a myth used to justify everything Israel has demanded
and obtained from Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi said that thinkers and freedom lovers all over the world
never expect such an act from a country as France who stakes
claims to human rights and freedom of expression and thought.
</P>
<P>
Iranian press also launched strong attack on the French
government over Garaudy's case.
</P>
<P>
Following the reports about Garaudy's trial, hundreds of
Iranian journalists and writers announced their support for the
French writer, saying that the trial was carried out under
political influence of Zionism in the west. 
</P>
</TEXT>
