<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 19 (Xinhua) -- With Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's flying to Washington for talks on the Middle
East peace process, U.S. President Bill Clinton said on Monday
that he had "high hopes" for revitalizing the deadlocked peace
negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"We're all going to have to make some moves if we're going to
get there," Clinton told reporters at the White House.
</P>
<P>
"I'm looking forward to the meeting. I'm committed to making it
a success," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Clinton met with his foreign policy advisers, aimed at
setting a tone for the upcoming talks with Netanyahu and Chairman
of Palestinian Authority Yasir Arafat, which will take place
separately on Tuesday and Thursday..
</P>
<P>
The 45-minute meeting included Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, National Security Adviser Sandy Berger, U.S. Middle East
envoy Dennis Ross and Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk,
White House spokesman Barry Toiv told reporters.
</P>
<P>
