<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Russia's Reaction to Turkish Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government Monday
welcomed Russia's response to an agreement signed recently
between Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot regime in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing here, Government
Spokesman Manolis Christofides said that "we endorse fully
Moscow's strong reaction to Ankara's decision to sign a
cooperation protocol with the so-called foreign ministry of the
illegal Turkish Cypriot regime."
</P>
<P>
The protocol was signed last week by the Turkish Cypriot
"Foreign and Defense Minister" Taner Etkin and Turkish Foreign
Ministry Under-Secretary Korkmaz Haktanir,
</P>
<P>
According to the protocol, diplomats of the self-proclaimed
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus (TRNC)" will take on duties
in Turkish embassies around the world for training purpose and
"TRNC" representatives will participate in Turkish delegations at
relevant meetings.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Valeri Nesteruskin was
quoted as saying last Saturday that the "signing of the protocol
for closer cooperation between the Turkish Foreign Ministry and
the illegal, secessionist fabrication (TRNC) will undoubtedly make
prospects in finding a just and viable Cyprus settlement more
difficult."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish move was regarded here as a step toward the
promised partial integration with northern Cyprus in response to
the European Union decision last month to start accession talks
with the Cypriot government in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island
following a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared the breakaway TRNC in 1983, which
was only recognized by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
