<HEADLINE> Cyprus Ready for Presidential Elections Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus is ready for the
presidential elections due to be held on February 8, said an
official press release issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the press release of the office of Cyprus' Chief
Returning Officer, more than 1,000 polling stations will operate
in five of the six districts in the country.
</P>
<P>
No polling will take place in Kyrenia as it is in the north of
the Mediterranean island controlled by the Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops took
over the northern third to protect the Turkish Cypriot minorities
after a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The press release said four polling stations in the districts
of Nicosia, Limassol, Larnaca and Paphos will operate specially
for the Greek Cypriots, mainly elderly, who live in the north.
</P>
<P>
More than 410,000 voters at the age of 18 and above will cast
ballot in the presidential elections, which is compulsory by law.
</P>
<P>
Seven candidates including incumbent President Glafcos
Clerides will run for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution, if no candidate secures more than 50
percent of the votes, the two front-runners will compete in a
run-off on the following Sunday, or February 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
