<HEADLINE> Greece Urges Turkey to Refrain From Using Military Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Greece today called on
neighboring Turkey to refrain from using military force as it had
done up to now, describing the use of force as unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that irregular military action contributed to
the deterioration of relations between Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He described the position adopted by Turkey concerning the
holding of military exercises in the Aegean as "irrational" and
"much more than inconsistent."
</P>
<P>
Recently, Turkey has conducted a series of large-scale military
exercises in the eastern Aegean and Turkish jet fighters have
continued to violate Greek airspace, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here do not rule out the possibility of a
direct military conflict between the two countries in the Aegean
in the future.
</P>
<P>
Reppas said that Greece was not proposing any moratorium but
wanted Turkey to show good faith by respecting international law
and international treaties.
</P>
<P>
As for the banning of the Turkish main opposition Welfare
Party, he said that such a decision might cause further political
instability in the neighboring country and consequently affect
Greek-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
He added that the banning of the biggest party in Turkey's
parliament illustrated once again the "lack of democracy" in the
country and confirmed that institutions were not functioning in
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Turkey's judiciary dissolved the Welfare Party and
imposed a five-year political ban on former Prime Minister and
party leader Necmettin Erbakan in an anti-Islamist crackdown.
</P>
