<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Angolan Govt Strives to Restore Railways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 19 (Xinhua) -- To rehabilitate economy and
promote development, the Angolan government has been striving
hard in the recent years to restore the country's railway
transport cut short by the civil war for over seven years.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Transport has revealed that in the first half
of this year, trains will once again arrive in the northern city
of Malanje and Menongue in the southeast.
</P>
<P>
Railway had been a major means of transportation in Angola,
with a total length of 2,900 km. There are the Luanda Railway in
the north, Namibe Railway in the south and Benguela Railway
crossing the central part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Benguela, as the most important railway in Angola with a
length of 1,340 km, passes grain-producing Bie and Huambo
provinces and further connects itself with the railway network in
the Democratic Republic of Congo and Zambia, thus becoming a key
line in southern Africa, transporting a large part of mineral
products from Congo (K) and copper ore from Zambia.
</P>
<P>
However, the 19-year-long civil war in Angola has devastated
its railway system, with nearly all of it in a paralyzed state. A
big section of the railway cannot work because of the mines.
Consequently air transport, expensive and limited as it is,
became a major way for transport.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government, in its bid to pave the way for
economic development, has invested 15 million U.S. Dollars to
restore the Luanda line in the north. After three years' efforts,
passenger and cargo transport is now resumed from Luanda to
Dondo, capital city of Kuanza-Norte province.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, repair work is in full swing on the
Luanda-Malanje line so that it will be opened for operation in
the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The 420-km line from Namibe to Matala, Huila province in the
south has been the longest operating line in the country. To
ensure its operation, the government has put in over 400 million
Dollars for the repair work. It is expected that the
Matala-Menongue section will start its operation by mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
What is more, research is undertaken by Angola to connect the
Namibe line with railways in neighboring Namibia. Once the
feasibility study is completed, the government will build the
railway through international bidding.
</P>
<P>
The Benguela line only has 30 km working now. The repair on
the whole line takes a total of 100 million Dollars. The Angolan
government has decided to cooperate with Italy to restore the
line under an agreement signed in October 1997. According to the
Ministry of Transport, repair work on the line will begin this
year.
</P>
<P>
With the consolidation of peace in the war-torn country,
Angola will usher in a period of large-scaled construction, which
will include the export of industrial and agricultural products
to the sea ports from the central region and import of raw
materials from the other way round.
</P>
<P>
The country's railways, once re-opened after rehabilitation,
will surely help the transport of products and raw materials in
the country so as to boost its national economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PC Sales to Continue Advancing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Sales of the personal computer
in the United States are forecast to grow from 31.9 million units
in 1997 to 49.2 million in 2001 as the machines are getting
cheaper, industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
PC Sales could grow by 15 percent to 36.7 million units this
year and the robust trend may go on till 2001 with 1999 expected
to see sales reaching 41.3 million units and another 45.3 million
are projected for 2000, a local newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The Investor's Business Daily, citing figures from industry
sources, said the trend could be helped by the fast-growing market
where the PC penetration into American homes may rise from 43
percent in 1997 to 45.5 percent this year and 51.4 percent in
2001.
</P>
<P>
The market is seeing more consumers because falling technology
prices in the 1990s have benefited PC retailers and wholesalers by
creating new markets for their products such as today's sub-1000
U.S. dollar computers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that average PC prices fell from around 1,700
dollars per unit in mid-1996 to about 1,300 dollars per unit at
the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sub-800 dollar PCs are hitting the market and some even expect
sub-500 dollar PCs to come out by early 1999.
</P>
<P>
More mergers and acquisitions are expected to take place in the
PC industry amid fierce competition and higher-end PCs could find
more orders when narrow margins of lower-end products are not
attractive to retailers, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Meeting on Mine Clearance Postponed to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Minister of Foreign
Affairs and Cooperation Leonardo Simao announced today that the
meeting of Regional De-mining Commission of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) will be postponed to February.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, due originally at the end of this month here, is
put off because of organizational problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
Simao made the announcement here at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Preparation for the meeting, he noted, has not been completed.
According the minister, when the meeting starts in February, a
regional program for mine clearance will be made and coordination
word in this regard has been put in the charge of Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Simao believed that Mozambique was chosen for the venue of the
meeting because it is one of the most affected countries in the
region and that it has made "remarkable progress" in de-mining.
</P>
<P>
Simao revealed that a total of 20 million mines had been
planted in southern Africa, half of which were in Angola.
</P>
<P>
About two million mines were planted in Mozambique during the
16-year-long civil war, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
