<HEADLINE> Controversial French Writer to Visit Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The controversial French writer
Roger Garaudy, who is standing trial in France on anti-Semitism
charges, will arrive here on February 12 for a visit to Egypt, the
Middle East News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Invited by Egyptian Minister of Culture Farouk Hosni, Garaudy
will meet on the same day of his arrival with Egyptian thinkers
and intellectuals at a symposium held by organizers of the annual
Cairo Book Fair which will start on February 5.
</P>
<P>
Garaudy stood trial before a Paris criminal court last week on
charges of trivializing the alleged Nazi Holocaust of Jews in
World War II.
</P>
<P>
Garaudy, who denies any wrongdoing, was brought to trial after
several anti-racism groups accused him of denying crimes against
humanity in his book "The Founding Myths of Israeli Politics."
</P>
<P>
Garaudy has argued that Hitler's killing of Jews amounted to
"massacres," but it was an exaggeration to call the Nazi crimes
"genocide" or a "Holocaust." He also ruled out that 6 million Jews
were killed.
</P>
<P>
An official of the General Egyptian Book Organization said
Garaudy was invited to Egypt "in a concrete gesture of solidarity
with the Muslim man (Garaudy) who is facing trial because he dared
to air his views on Zionism."
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Writers Union has issued a statement in support of
Garaudy and of human rights and free speech. The Egyptian Women
Writers Association sent a plea to French intellectuals to support
Garaudy during his trial.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Garaudy's wife Salma el-Farouk hosted
earlier this week a banquet for Egyptian writers and intellectuals
in Cairo to lobby support for her husband. 
</P>
</TEXT>
