<HEADLINE> Gore Proposes New Measures against Discrimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
today unveiled a White House initiative to step up efforts against
discrimination in employment and housing during a commemorative
service at an Atlanta church where slain civil rights leader Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr. preached.
</P>
<P>
Gore said the Clinton administration plans "the largest single
increase in the enforcement of our civil rights laws in nearly two
decades." There would be "new reforms and heightened commitment to
enforcement," he added.
</P>
<P>
Aides said a Clinton budget to be presented to Congress next
month would include an 86 million dollar increase in spending to
target employers and landlords who discriminate based on race or
color, according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
The proposal would increase the use of mediators in an effort
to cut a backlog of 64,000 discrimination cases pending at the
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
Gore said, "Dr. King would not let us forget that
African-Americans still earn roughly 62 cents on each dollar that
white Americans earn. He would not let us forget that black
unemployment is still twice as high as unemployment for whites."
</P>
<P>
Gore spoke from the pulpit at an annual ecumenical service at
Ebenezer Baptist Church, where King worshiped as a child. He
co-pastored the church with his father from 1960 until he was
assassinated in Memphis, Tennessee, in 1968.
</P>
<P>
The service, attended by numerous dignitaries, marked the 69th
birthday of the slain civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
The Atlanta service was one of dozens held across the country
to honor King. 
</P>
