<HEADLINE> Oil Spill Expands in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The oil spill in southeast
Nigeria's Akwa Ibom State caused by a pipeline leakage, has
expanded to the Bayelsa State to the west, the News Agency of
Nigeria said today.
</P>
<P>
A statement signed by Yomi Adeyemi-Wilson, the external
affairs manager of the Mobil Producing Nigerian Unlimited, said
oil patches have been found in the mouth of the Pennington River
and in a fishing village.
</P>
<P>
"Patches of oil were found on the beach, large patches for
about 500 feet with small patches extending for about a mile,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The spill, the worst ever in Nigeria, occurred last Monday
when one of the pipelines linking Mobil's "Idomo" oil field and
its Qua Iboe Export Terminal ruptured.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 40,000 barrels of crude oil are
spilled. The accident also halted oil delivery at the terminal.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, Mobil is working with the state
and local government agencies with assurance that the company is
taking all appropriate measures to clean up the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Company sources said earlier that about half of the spilled
oil have been cleaned up by last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Western oil companies operating in Nigeria have tense
relations with their operating communities, which have been
demanding compensations for environment damages resulting from
constant spills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
