<HEADLINE> Islamic Party Leader Calls Court Ruling Mistake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Turkish pro-Islamic politician
Necmettin Erbakan said Monday that the Constitutional Court made
"a serious mistake" by ordering the closure of the Welfare Party
(RP) led by him.
</P>
<P>
There is no legal reason to shut down the RP which was set up
in accordance with the law, Erbakan told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is a state based on law. The mistake of the (court)
decision will be corrected," Erbakan said.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the Constitutional Court, the country's supreme
judicial organ, announced the closure of the RP on the ground of
its anti-secular stand.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, Erbakan and several other RP leaders were also
deprived of their parliamentarian status and will be banned from
engaging in politics for five years.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan met with Bulent Ecevit and Husamettin Cindoruk,
chairmen of two major political parties in the Parliament before
the press conference, but declined to give details of the talks.
Erbakan said he is not intending to rally support against the
Constitutional Court decision.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, also former Turkish prime minister, is expected to
meet other parliamentary party leaders and Parliament Speaker
Hikmet Cetin as well.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan and his RP have long been accused by the powerful
Turkish military of undermining the country's secular and
democratic systems. As a result, the RP-led coalition government
was forced to step down last summer.
</P>
<P>
The RP, however, denied the charges, saying that it has no plan
to shake Turkey's secularism.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court's ruling on the closure of the RP
also aroused concern from other political parties, which held
that it is so rash to shut down the RP, the largest political
party in the country.
</P>
<P>
The RP followers also organized rallies around the country to
protest against the court decision, but no clashes have been
reported so far.
</P>
<P>
RP Deputy Chairman Ahmet Tekdal said last Friday that no
matter what happens, the party will continue to advance its
course. 
</P>
</TEXT>
