<HEADLINE> Death Rate Rises Swiftly in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The death rate of Iraqi
children and the elderly last December rose swiftly, the Iraqi
News Agency (INA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the Iraqi Health Ministry,
6,163 children below five died last December of diarrhea pleurisy
and malnutrition, compared to 299 children in the same month of
1989.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, 2,459 elderly above 50 died of
hypertension, diabetes and malignant tumors, compared to 419 in
December, 1989.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Health Ministry attributed the rise of the death rate
of children and the elderly to the diseases caused by the acute
shortage of food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
According to Iraqi official statistics, more than 1.5 million
Iraqis have died since 1990 when the crippling economic sanctions
were imposed on Iraq by the United Nations after its invasion of
Kuwait. 
</P>
