<HEADLINE> WHO Executive Board to Nominate New Director-General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The 101st session of the
Executive Board of the World Health Organization (WHO) began here
today with the nomination of a new director-general among its
agenda.
</P>
<P>
The nomination, voted in closed session, is expected to be
announced on January 27. The nomination by the Executive Board
will then be considered by the World Health Assembly in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
Top items in the agenda during the two-week session include the
draft global health policy for the 21st century and WHO reform,
according to a WHO press release.
</P>
<P>
The new global health policy for the 21st century "Health for
All in the 21st Century" builds on past achievements, guides
action and policy for health at all levels, and identifies global
priorities and targets.
</P>
<P>
Other items to be discussed are emerging and other communicable
diseases, noncommunicable disease prevention and control, strategy
on sanitation for high-risk communities, climate change and human
health, tropical diseases, and infant and young child nutrition,
tuberculosis, prevention of violence and cooperation with
nongovernmental organizations. 
