<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Cautiously Backs Italy's Place in EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) finance
and economic ministers today cautiously backed Italy for joining
the economic and monetary union (EMU) after they approved its
projections for public finances.
</P>
<P>
The EU's finance and economic ministers arrived in Brussels
today to attend the first Ecofin meeting held since Britain took
over the rotating EU presidency in January. They were scheduled
to discuss EMU and the Asian crisis at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here today, the EU said measures outlined
in Italy's 1998 budget should keep its deficit below the
EMU-required 3 percent of GDP (gross domestic product), indicating
that progress achieved in 1997 was sustainable.
</P>
<P>
"The council considered that the measures included in the 1998
budget should allow the deficit target of 2.8 percent to be
achieved," the EU said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The EU also encouraged Italy to vigorously implement the budget
in order to reduce its deficit to 1.8 percent of GDP in the year
2000, which is targeted in its convergence program.
</P>
<P>
However, Germany and the Netherlands still maintain their
neutral position on the cautious support expressed by the council
for Italy's place in EMU. They were the two major critics in the
past of Italy's budgetary performance.
</P>
<P>
They insisted they said nothing about the decision EU leaders
have to take on participants of the first wave of EMU in May,
which is going to be launched in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
But the two countries admitted that Italy had done a better job
in cleaning up its finances. "We don't have a special position on
Italy. We have no historical or geographical prejudgement as far
as Italy is concerned," said Dutch Finance Minister Gerrit Zalm.
</P>
<P>
Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi indicated that
Germany and the Netherlands should have had no difficulty in
approving the Ecofin statement.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism about Italy's prospects for joining the
EMU at its launch, adding that "the question of post-EMU
sustainability" remained a problem for all.
</P>
<P>
Italy's huge debt has become its biggest headache. Standing at
123 percent of GDP, it is more than twice the reference of 60
percent set in the Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Ciampi said the Italian authorities would try to cut the debt
by 2002 to 100 percent of GDP and reduce it further to 60 percent
by 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
