<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Finance Ministers Stress Need for Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing financial crisis
in Asia has shown that Europe should be united in order to have a
stronger voice in world affairs and a better defense against
global financial turmoil, European Union finance and economic
ministers said here today.
</P>
<P>
The ministers arrived in Brussels today for the first Ecofin
meeting ever held since Britain took over the rotating EU
presidency in January. They also discussed the planned single
currency on the same day.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the planned single currency in 1999 would add to
global stability and reinforce Europe's international role, French
Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn said at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He held out hopes that the euro would make the voices of EU
countries be heard "much more loudly and clearly in the world."
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the EU needed to ensure Europe was still a
"pole of stability" in a time of instability in Asia. "We need
stability in Asia, but we also need it in Europe," said the French
minister.
</P>
<P>
Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi expressed the
same view by saying, "Europe must have a greater voice in world
affairs. The crisis in Asia has shown that Europe has a role and
we must reinforce this."
</P>
<P>
Their Belgian counterpart, Philippe Maystadt, suggested that a
new group be set up to study what kind of role the euro could play
in the international monetary system.
</P>
<P>
However, most EU finance ministers said they saw no real danger
of a severe impact on Europe growth from the crisis.
</P>
<P>
But British Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordan Brown, who
chaired today's meeting, told reporters that the EU had to be
always alert to what was happening in Asia since, as he said,
"Europe has a higher volume of exports to the region than the
United States, a greater banking exposure than the United States
and Japan combined."
</P>
<P>
The Asian region is now being haunted by a creeping spread of
devaluation, payments problems and financial market instability.
International institutions such as the International Monetary Fund
has been forced to wade in to help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
