<HEADLINE> Talks Between British Prime Minister, Sinn Fein </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The talks between Prime Minister
Tony Blair and Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams on Monday in Downing
Street was "constructive and worthwhile," the British prime
minister's official spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"They agreed that recent killings are an attempt to derail the
process and that we must not be deflected from the democratic and
peaceful path," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the second between Blair and Adams in recent
weeks, the prime minister said he was absolutely committed to the
process and it was a government priority to save the fragile peace
process, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Blair and Adams used "virtually the same words" in
condemning the wave of tit-for-tat killings since Christmas.
</P>
<P>
A prominent pro-British Protestant was killed in his carpet
shop on the outskirts of Belfast hours before Blair met with
Adams. And soon after the meeting, a Catholic taxi driver died in
hospital in Belfast after suffering five gunshot wounds in his
upper body.
</P>
<P>
Blair stressed that the most recent Anglo-Irish peace plan,
which Sinn Fein has rejected, was merely a basis for negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the meeting, Adams said the talks were frank, but
he told Blair that Sinn Fein rejected a new Anglo-Irish peace
proposal.
</P>
<P>
Anyone who thought proposals for a power-sharing assembly in
Northern Ireland would work was not "living in the real world," he
told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
