<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Proposes Higher Spending on Civil Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Marking the Martin Luther
King Jr. holiday Monday, U.S. Vice President Al Gore proposed
increasing civil rights spending.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration will propose spending 602 million
dollars to enforce civil rights laws in the 1999 budget, up from
516 million dollars this year, Gore said at Ebenezer Baptist
Church in Atlanta, Georgia, King's hometown.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere across the country, the slain civil rights leader was
honored with prayers, service projects, parades and, for the first
time, a halt in trading on U.S. financial markets. King turned 69
last week.
</P>
<P>
Gore said the proposed civil rights spending boost will include
a 22 million-dollar increase for the Department of Housing and
Urban Development to fight housing discrimination. Other changes
would strengthen investigations of police brutality and
enforcement of the Americans With Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
Details will be included in the budget to be submitted by
President Bill Clinton next month.
</P>
<P>
King "would be proud to see how much we have done to banish
discrimination from our laws. But I believe he would tell us that
we still have much to do in banishing discrimination from our
hearts," Gore was quoted as saying by new reports.
</P>
<P>
The service was one of hundreds of events around the country
honoring King three decades after his assassination in Memphis,
Tennessee, on April 4, 1968.
</P>
<P>
Clinton helped renovate a school in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred people in St. Louis observed the day at
ceremony at the Old Courthouse where the Dred Scott case, a
pivotal test of pre-Civil War slavery law, was tried more than 150
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Monday was the first ever King holiday for Ocoee, Florida,
where a 1920 race riot killed at least six people and drove blacks
away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
