<HEADLINE> EU Approves Humanitarian Aid for China Quake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
today it had approved humanitarian aid worth 525,000 ECUs (some
630,000 U.S. dollars) for victims of a recent earthquake in the
Hebei province of northeastern China.
</P>
<P>
The quake, which took place on January 10, reportedly killed 50
people, injured about 10,000 and left tens of thousands homeless
(please check).
</P>
<P>
The EU said on the same day that it had also approved
humanitarian aid for victims of El Nino, a warming Pacific Ocean
current which disrupts climate pattern, in Andean countries.
</P>
<P>
The EU's executive body, the European Commission, said it had
rushed through humanitarian aid worth 4.1 million ECUs (about 4.8
million dollars) for the El Nino victims.
</P>
<P>
El Nino has caused widespread damage across the globe in recent
months, including heavy flooding in South America and raging bush
fires in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The aid would enable European non-governmental organizations
(NGOs) to carry out emergency aid programs in Ecuador, Peru and
Bolivia, the EU executive said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Commission has also approved humanitarian aid worth 10
million ECUs (12 million dollars) for regions of Poland and the
Czech Republic which suffered catastrophic floods last summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
