<HEADLINE> Inmate Population Rises in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The number of inmates in U.S.
jails and prisons reached more than 1.7 million last June, local
press reported today, citing official figures.
</P>
<P>
The incarceration rate of the United States stood at 645 per
100,000 people in 1997, compared to 313 per 100,000 in 1985, the
New York Times quoted a Justice Department study as saying.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, jails house those awaiting trail or serving
terms of less than a year, while prisons are considered as those
holding convicts serving longer sentences.
</P>
<P>
Drug offenses have accounted for over a third of the growth in
the incarcerated people since early 1970s and the incarceration
rate for drug arrests has climbed 1,000 percent since 1980,
criminologist Alfred Blumsterin was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the incarceration rate for drug offenders alone
accounts for about 145 per 100,000 today.
</P>
<P>
Professor John J. DiIulio Jr of Princeton University said he
has found that 25 percent of the new inmates in New York State are
drug-only offenders, not involving other types of crimes.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the proportion of criminals entering the
prison for the second or more time has gone up steadily since
1980. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
