<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Mission Sets Out for Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- A European Union (EU)
investigation team today set out for a 24-hour mission to Algeria
for unprecedented talks with its authorities on six years of
bloodshed in the oil-rich North African state.
</P>
<P>
The three junior ministers, led by British junior foreign
minister Derek Fatchett and accompanied by European Commissioner
Manual Marin, were due to arrive in Algiers later on Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett and his counterparts from Luxembourg and Austria will
meet Algerian Foreign Minister Ahmed Attaf, opposition members of
parliament and newspaper editors before returning home late on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss a wave of massacres that has taken the lives
of more than 1,100 men, women and children in the past three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time the Algerian government has showed
willingness to discuss the conflict with the international
community.
</P>
<P>
After repeatedly rejecting such discussions as interference in
its internal affairs, Algeria agreed to the mission under intense
pressure, but stood firm on its insistence that the talks should
focus on joint efforts to confront "terrorism".
</P>
<P>
Algiers has also rejected any inquiry into the massacres, for
which, as for the rest of the six-year-old conflict, it blames
Muslim rebels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
