<HEADLINE> Stratigis Elected to Lead Athens 2004 Organizing Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Greece announced on Monday that
Stratis Stratigis would head the Athens 2004 Organizing Committee
of the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
said that the country had decided to establish two committees,
namely the National Olympic Committee and the Athens 2004
Organizing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Under the Aegis of Greek President Costis Stephanopoulos, the
National Olympic Commitee would monitor preparation and evaluate
the work carried out.
</P>
<P>
The main responsibility for organization and execution of the
works would be undetaken by the Athens 2004 Organizing Commitee,
which would operate as a societe anonyme, to be headed by the
64-year-old Stratigis, a lawyer and former new democracry and
democratic renewal parliamentarian.
</P>
<P>
It was the Greek government's desire to set up "an efficient
and flexible scheme" which would guarantee the preparation and
execution of the games under a regime of absolute transparency and
control, he said, adding that "this set-up meets that aspiration,
as Greece's goal is to prove that it is capable of successfully
completing the task it has undertaken."
</P>
<P>
Gianna Angelopoulos-Daskalaki, who headed the Athens 2004
Bidding Committee, would be a member of the National Olympic
Committee after her personal request not to participate in the
organizing committee for "personal reasons."
</P>
<P>
In early September last year, Athens won the right to stage the
2004 summer Olympic Games after defeating the other four cities
such as Rome, Cape Town, Stockholm and Buenos Aires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
