<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summer Palace, Temple of Heaven Bid for World Heritage Honor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has
applied for the inclusion of Beijing's Summer Palace and Temple of
Heaven on UNESCO's World Heritage List.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization (UNESCO) will inspect the two sites next
month.
</P>
<P>
The Summer Palace, initiated in the mid-18th century, was
burned by the British and French Joint Forces in 1860 and rebuilt
in 1886. Famous for its buildings combined with mountains and
lakes, China's largest imperial garden attracts 40-50 million
tourists a year.
</P>
<P>
Located in the southern part of Beijing, the Temple of Heaven
was where emperors of the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911)
dynasties worshipped for a good harvest. It is an example of
ancient sacrificial structure.
</P>
<P>
China has 19 sites on the World Heritage List, including the
Great Wall and the Forbidden City. The Suzhou Gardens in east
China's Jiangsu Province was added to the list last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks Only Way Forward in N.Ireland, Says Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Kingdom's Northern
Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam appealed on Tuesday to all parties
involved in the peace talks in Northern Ireland to be ready to
change their stance.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on BBC Radio 4, Mowlam said negotiation was "the way
we are going to deal with extremists on both sides."
</P>
<P>
Despite the violence in the divided province in recent weeks,
the British government would seek to do everything possible to
move the talks forward, she said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary also vowed to stand firm against a wave of
sectarian revenge killings in Northern Ireland, saying the
government would not allow splinter guerrilla groups to derail the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I am determined not to let our will be broken by these
splinter-groups...who are just interested in breaking the peace
talks," the secretary said.
</P>
<P>
A Roman Catholic taxi driver was shot dead on Monday in the
third tit-for-tat killing in the troubled province, the seventh
bloody murder since Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The killings overshadowed the talks in London between Prime
Minister Tony Blair and leaders of Sinn Fein, the Irish Republican
Army's political wing.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams told reporters after the talks
with Blair that his party rejected the proposal for a
power-sharing assembly for Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"Anyone who thinks an internal settlement is going to work, or
some assembly with a few nationalist knobs stuck on to it is going
to work is not living in the real world," Adams said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
