<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK in Urgent Need of Foreign Food Aid: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Because of summer's serious
drought, the amount of food per person in the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) from October 1997 to September 1998 is a
mere 180 grams a day, a senior official says.
</P>
<P>
Cha Limsok, deputy director of the Farm Produce Bureau of the
Agricultural Commission under the Administration Council, said
DPRK people were in urgent need of international help. He was
speaking in a recent interview with the Xinhua News Agency.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time the DPRK had revealed such statistics to
the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Cha said the DPRK's gross grain output in 1997 amounted to
2.685 million tons, which was processed into 2.148 million tons of
cereals.
</P>
<P>
The minimum need for grain between October 1997 and September
1998 is estimated at 4.022 million tons, but this figure falls
short by 60 percent now, he said.
</P>
<P>
After deducting seeds and feed grains, the country only had
1.422 million tons of grain in storage by the end of September
last year.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to make good the food deficit, the central government
plans to import 500,000 tons of grain and will appeal to the
international community for another 700,000 tons of aid in grain.
</P>
<P>
The disaster area hit by summer's drought covers 466,000
hectares of cultivated land in the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
In late August, the country's western coastal grain-producing
region was struck by typhoon and tsunami. These caused an
additional grain loss of 700,000 tons. The number of victims of
the natural calamities totaled 2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
Cha said the DPRK government and the people will try their best
to achieve a good harvest in 1998, but are still short of more
than 7,000 tons of barley seeds, 1000 tons of corn seeds and
considerable amounts of chemical fertilizers and pesticides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
