<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corruption Stays Under Control in HK: Yam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Corruption has continued to
be effectively contained in Hong Kong after the handover, Lily Yam
Kwan Pui-ying, the commissioner of the Independent Commission
Against Corruption (ICAC), said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some people had worried about a deterioration of corruption in
the newly established Special Administrative Region (SAR), but
things have turned out to be different, Yam said.
</P>
<P>
Great efforts made by the ICAC staff and the wide support from
the local community are viewed as major reasons why Hong Kong
stays a clean place.
</P>
<P>
ICAC figures revealed that in the year 1997, corruption reports
(excluding election reports) received by the ICAC totaled 3,057,
down 1 percent compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
A high 68 percent of people gave their names when reporting to
the ICAC, demonstrating their confidence in the
corruption-fighting body, Yam noted.
</P>
<P>
Of the total reports, 512 reports or some 17 percent were
related to the police force, down 11 percent from the previous
year's 576 reports.
</P>
<P>
Around half of the reports were related to the private sector,
in particular the construction sector, the financial sector and
the property sector. "The ICAC will intensify preventive
education in the business sector this year," Yam pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The remaining reports concerned other government departments
and public bodies.
</P>
<P>
A total of 314 people were prosecuted in 1997, dropping 8
percent from 1996, while 208 people were convicted, down 14
percent. But government servants recommended for consideration of
disciplinary or administrative action soared by 60 percent to
total 356.
</P>
<P>
Cross-border corruption recorded 74 cases in 1997, down from 92
cases in 1996. Yam pointed out that the ICAC will continue its
cooperation with authorities on China's inland areas, in
particular the neighboring Guangdong province, in the crackdown on
the cross-border corruption.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Provides Technical Assistance to Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has agreed to grant a technical assistance of 500,000 U.S.
dollars to assist the Nepali government in strengthening its
project performance management system, the ADB said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The technical assistance will support the establishment of an
accountable and result-oriented institutional framework for the
programming, budgeting and management of development projects, the
bank said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The improved procedures and systems will enable the Nepali
government to formulate and prioritize projects based on clear
development criteria, implement and monitor these projects
effectively by keeping track of and comparing project results with
actual and expected outputs and impacts, identify implementation
issues for timely and necessary corrective actions, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
The press release noted that Nepal is a resource-constrained
country, so there is a need to improve the efficiency of
utilization of the available resources, which can be achieved
through prioritization of development projects and strengthening
of project formulation and management capacity.
</P>
<P>
The ADB is a member of the Nepal Aid Group.  
</P>
</TEXT>
