and good to try out a lot of things."
</P>
<P>
Hingis is back at the scene of her major breakthrough, the
place where the 17-year-old Swiss collected her first major
tournament.
</P>
<P>
She went on last year to capture Wimbledon and the US Open,
thus becoming the third teenager after Steffi Graf and Monica
Seles to win three or more grand slam singles titles in one year.
</P>
<P>
Hingis' main worry shouldn't come until the fourth round where
she is on track for a meeting with Belgian Dominique Van Roost,
the No.14 seed.
</P>
<P>
Van Roost's best grand slam performance was here last year when
she reached the quarter-finals and was forced to retire with an
abdominal strain while trailing Mary Joe Fernandez 7-5, 4-0.
</P>
<P>
In Wednesday's match, Van Roost beat Canadian Rene Simpson 6-3,
6-2 to move into the second round but was given treatment by a
trainer at courtside for what appeared to be a shoulder complaint.
</P>
<P>
Russian teenager Anna Kournikova swept into round two with a
speedy 6-2, 6-1 win over Slovakian Katarina Studenikova and at the
other end of the spectrum Czech veteran Helena Sukova bowed out of
singles tennis with a 4-6, 7-5, 6-0 loss to American Anne Miller.
