<HEADLINE> ADB Supports Asian Countries' Banking Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
announced Tuesday that it has approved a technical assistance
grant of 2.6 million U.S. dollars to selected Asian countries for
banking, capital market and international competitiveness reforms.
</P>
<P>
The technical assistance, to be funded from the
ADB-administered Japan Special Fund, comes in the wake of the
severe financial turbulence which has rocked the region for more
than six months.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank had earlier announced contributions to
the support packages for Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea
totaling around 8.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The technical assistance will be implemented initially for a
period of one year this year, with possible additional funding for
two years, the ADB said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Specialists will assist the selected countries' finance,
planning, trade and industry ministries in designing and
implementing sector reforms and programs.
</P>
<P>
The consultants will also submit a comprehensive report on how
the crisis was handled through sector reforms at the end of the
first year.
</P>
<P>
An interdepartmental task force on financial sector reform has
already been established by the ADB in response to the recent
economic and financial upheavals. 
</P>
