<HEADLINE> Businesses Call for Protection of Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-four large and
super-large manufacturing businesses in eight provinces along the
Yangtze River have called for less pollution of the longest river
in China.
</P>
<P>
At a forum to protect the Yangtze River, also Asia's longest
and the world's third longest, held recently in Wuhan, a hub on
the middle reaches of the river, representatives of the businesses
urged factories in the Yangtze River Valley to reduce their
discharge of wastes and polluting materials into the river,
according to Beijing-based China Women's News.
</P>
<P>
They also suggested that the state enact laws and regulations
to protect the Yangtze from further pollution.
</P>
<P>
About 15 billion tons of waste water is discharged into the
Yangtze and its tributaries each year, according to the Bureau of
Protection of Water Resources in the Yangtze Valley.
</P>
<P>
And 70 percent of the waste water dumped into the Yangtze are
from industrial sources, and large and super-large factories are
responsible for 80 percent of the industrial waste water.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four of 59 major cities in the valley have a water
shortage as a result of the pollution, and experts predict the
problem will be exacerbated with further economic expansion of the
river.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
