<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science Data Base Now Available on Home Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A multi-media data base
consultation system developed to replace the traditional
exhibition fair has opened today in Beijing. The system offers
access from home to China's 60,000 major pieces of scientific data
collected during the 1991-1995 period.
</P>
<P>
As a key technical project in China's Eighth Five-Year Plan
period (1991-1995), the multi-media system passed an expert
assessment today and was put into use by the State Planning
Commission (SPC).
</P>
<P>
Lu Da, deputy director of the Optical Memory National
Engineering Research Center of Qinghua University, said the giant
system contains information on video and audio frequencies as well
as graphics and characters equaling the storage of 60 optical
disks.
</P>
<P>
Lu, who participated in the development of the system, said any
overseas subscriber can gain access via the Internet with SPC
authorization.
</P>
<P>
China used to held an exhibition fair every five years to
display its scientific achievements at a cost of at least 10
million yuan (1.2 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
An official from the SPC said the system not only keeps
scientific documents on record and replaces the exhibition fair,
but also accelerates their promotion.
</P>
<P>
China has poured nine billion yuan (1.08 billion U.S. dollars)
into 180 major scientific research programs in the Eighth
Five-Year Plan period, and reaped an economic return of more than
60 billion yuan (7.2 million U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
