<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: British Man to Bicycle Along Yellow River (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a photographer, he is already anticipating a variety of
natural landscapes along the river, which got "yellow" in its name
because of the muddy water.
</P>
<P>
He expects to take in focus the fertile flat on the lower
reaches of the river, the Loess Plateau at the middle, a vast
desert area where Genghis Khan's tomb lies and rocky Qinghai
Province, the source of the river.
</P>
<P>
Bishop's cycling on the Yellow River would be 500 miles further
away from his major of business management in a British
University. Since graduation, he worked nine years in a
company. Then he realized that he needed to be out in the nature
and quit his job. He spend the next three years traveling in
Africa, and then headed straight to the Silk Road in China, before
settling down in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Bishop said that his years of trekking on the fields and
tapping on the keyboards has been very rewarding and enhanced his
self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
"Five years ago, if someone had said to me, 'you can write a
book,' I would have thought they were mad. But I had the idea and
I had the desire to do the book, so I proved to myself that if you
want to do something, you'll find a way to do it, and if you work
hard enough, you succeed in doing something," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bishop hopes that his experiences would encourage "people who
have doubts that they maybe can't do something."
</P>
<P>
"If they really want to do something, they can find a way," he
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
