<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Anti-Narcotics Campaign Successful in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- In 1997 China's anti-drug
campaign scored its greatest achievement in recent years, said Tao
Siju, head of the State Anti-narcotics Committee and minister of
Public Security.
</P>
<P>
Gao said from January to November of 1997, public security
bureaus across the country uncovered 106,000 drug-related cases,
an increase of 29 percent over the historical record set in the
same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that during the same period, more than 135,000
drug traffickers and dealers had been captured by the national
police force, an increase of 57.8 percent over the historical
record in the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that, last year, Chinese police seized 1.9
tons of opium, 2.3 tons of marijuana, more than a ton of "ice,"
and 350 tons of drug-processing chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Gao said the law-enforcement agencies at all levels last year
dealt with more than 10,000 drug-related cases, and more than
16,000 suspects were in custody for further investigation. More
than 8,000 criminals were jailed from five years-to-life and some
received death sentences.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that China also has set up more than 690
drug-rehabilitation centers to offer mandatory treatment to drug
addicts. A record 90,000 drug addicts are being reformed at
rehabilitation camps run by the judicial departments, according to
Tao.
</P>
<P>
The minister called on concerned departments to seize the
golden opportunity to reinforce the anti-drug publicity campaign,
improve the anti-narcotics awareness of the whole nation and
strike a hard blow against drug-related crimes in accordance with
the law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
