<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Stone Structure Rivals Greek Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists claim
they have found a 2,000-year-old stone structure that rivals
ancient Greek or Roman relics.
</P>
<P>
The structure, a 200-meter stone canal connected with a pool,
was found at the site of the imperial palaces of the Nanyue
Kingdom which ruled over present-day Guangdong Province during the
Western Han Dynasty (206 BC-24 AD). The site is in downtown
Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
The canal, 1.4 meters wide, was made of stones that were paved
in a broken-ice crackle design. On the bottom were black cobbles
dotted with yellow ones.
</P>
<P>
Two stone dams were set up in the canal to create a spray.
</P>
<P>
To the eastern end of the canal was a pool in the shape of a
crescent moon. Among the silt at the bottom of the pool were
remains of hundreds of turtles, with the largest turtle shell
measuring 44 centimeters wide.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Beijing-based State Bureau of Cultural Relics
said that the stone structure was the same as that built in the
imperial palace complex of Liu Bang, the first emperor of the
Western Han Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that Liu built such a stone canal
between Changle and Weiyang palaces in Changan, present-day Xi'an,
capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province. No remnants of that
structure have ever been found.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Customs Achieves Fruitful Results in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Customs and
Excise Department had achieved "considerable" achievements in
various areas of work in the past year, Lawrence Li, commissioner
of customs and excise of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR), said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Protection of intellectual property rights was high on the list
of priorities of the department, Li said in a year-end statement
to review the department's work in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Additional resources were allocated to this area and new
legislation was introduced to strengthen enforcement capabilities
in the fight against copyright pirates, Li said.
</P>
<P>
During the year, the department arrested 1,568 persons in 1,473
cases for copyright offenses and 959 persons in 1,087 cases for
counterfeit offenses, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Value of goods seized amounted to 397.7 million HK dollars
(50.99 million U.S. dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Our most notable success was in driving the copyright pirates
out of the most notorious shopping arcades," Li said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the protection of intellectual property rights,
the department also achieved fruitful results in collecting
revenue, fighting smuggling and protecting consumers' interests,
Li said.
</P>
<P>
The department collected a total of 10,298.3 million HK dollars
(1,320.3 million U.S. dollars) of revenue in 1997, roughly six
percent of the government's annual income in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Li said that Hong Kong has maintained its full capability as a
customs service after the handover on July 1, 1997, and it
continued to function in the way that it was used to.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong customs department has maintained a healthy and
growing cooperative relationship with the colleagues in China's
inland areas, "but we make our own decisions," Li said.
</P>
<P>
"We have continued to participate in international conferences
and maintained and developed our relationship with other customs
administrations and law enforcement agencies around the world," he
added.
</P>
<P>
To prepare for the challenges in the years ahead, the
department is undergoing a process of modernization and has
already launched a number of new projects.
</P>
<P>
These include new computer systems, construction of a new
customhouse which will commerce in April this year, additional
customs launches, new installations for customs at the new airport
at Chek Lap Kok and planning for a customs headquarters
building. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
