<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: British Man to Bicycle Along Yellow River (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Yellow River book, like the book on the imperial way, will
have company sponsors' names, logos and even a CEO's speech, the
40-year-old man said.
</P>
<P>
Bishop, who has short silvery hair and black whiskers, chose to
write on the Yellow River, China's second longest river, instead
of the longer Yangtze, because much has been written about the
latter.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment everyone else is writing about Yangtze, because
it's a hot topic with the Three Gorges dam -- they talk about
environmental issues," he said. "In fact there already have been
several books on the Yangtze, from different angles."
</P>
<P>
In contrast, Bishop finds a blank area concerning information
on the Yellow River. He punched "Yellow River" on a computer but
nothing came up. In a library he got a mere couple of paragraphs
on the river from books writing about China.
</P>
<P>
"The Yellow River seems to have been neglected, but it's still
an important river, but nobody is writing about it at the moment,"
he said. "So I thought, well, it's high time it was written about
again."
</P>
<P>
Bishop believes that his second book, which is on the Yellow
River, would be more interesting and successful. The first book,
on the imperial way, had sold 5,000 copies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
