<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Wishes to Further Develop Ties With China: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine said on Monday that France wishes to further develop its
relations with China.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Chinese journalists on the eve of his
official visit to China scheduled for January 22-23, Vedrine said
that the Socialist government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
attaches as much importance to developing relations with China as
President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that during his visit to China in May last year,
President Chirac signed with Chinese President Jiang Zemin a joint
political declaration on establishing global partnership between
France and China.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said that France and China are two very important
countries in the world, and that both of them are permanent
members of the United Nations Security Council. Therefore, the
reinforcement of bilateral consultations and a comparison of their
views will contribute to the construction of a multipolar world,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there is no field of contention between France and
China and that his forthcoming visit to China will enable him to
discuss with Chinese leaders bilateral relations and international
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine also pointed out that economic relations between France
and China are insufficient as compared with the political
relations between them.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is necessary to redouble the efforts by both
sides to increase economic exchanges, especially in the field of
aeronautics, nuclear energy, financial service and agriculture and
food.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister stressed that France supports a useful
dialogue rather than confrontation over human rights with China.
</P>
<P>
He also reaffirmed that the French government is committed to
the 1994 Sino-French joint communique in which France promised not
to sell arms to Taiwan from then on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
