<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presidents of China, Benin Hold Talks in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
here today held talks with Benin President Mathieu Kerekou,
exchanging opinions on bilateral relations and other issues of
common interests in a cordial and friendly atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Jiang welcomed Kerekou to China for the third time, and said
that Kerekou is the first foreign head of state to visit China in
the new year. The Benin president is a familiar and respectable
friend of the Chinese people, Jiang said, who has greatly
contributed to the promotion of mutual understanding and
friendship between the two nations and their peoples.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said he believed the Benin president's visit would
further the development of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that since the restoration of diplomatic relations
25 years ago, the peoples of China and Benin have respected each
other, trusted each other and supported each other. The two
nations have demonstrated friendly and fruitful cooperation in
such areas as politics, trade, military and culture, he said.
</P>
<P>
The friendship between China and Benin has withstood the test
of time and a changeable world situation, Jiang stressed, adding
that China was satisfied with the development of their bilateral
friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China and Benin, both developing countries, share many common
interests in international affairs, and have cooperated in the
United Nations and other multi-lateral areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must thank the president and Benin government for their
constant support to China on human right issues and on China's
entry into the World Trade Organization," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"The president attaches great importance to the friendship with
China, adheres to the 'one China' policy, and supports China's
reunification cause."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government and people treasure the traditional
friendship with Benin, Jiang said, adding that on the basis of
Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence, China is ready to join
with Benin to further develop long-term and stable, sincere and
friendly bilateral links of overall cooperation geared to the
future. The two countries should constantly advance the bilateral
friendship and cooperative ties to a new stage, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presidents of China, Benin Hold Talks in Beijing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kerekou recalled his visit to China in 1986. He said he felt
honored to be granted an interview with the great Deng Xiaoping,
who was a great friend to African people, and toward whom the
African people cherish a feeling of great reverence.
</P>
<P>
Kerekou said China provided valuable assistance to Benin during
the past 25 years. Many places in Benin carry the mark of China's
assistance in helping to build and develop the country.
</P>
<P>
China also supported Benin's fight for independence and
sovereignty, he said, offering on behalf of the Benin government
and people his sincere thanks to China.
</P>
<P>
China is Benin's most sincere friend, he said. The friendship
between the two nations will exist for a long time no matter what
happens, he said, and Benin will always be China's reliable friend.
</P>
<P>
There is only one China in the world, he said, and the Benin
government recognizes the Government of the People's Republic of
China as the sole legitimate government on behalf of all the
Chinese people and Taiwan as one of its provinces. Benin firmly
supports China's bid for reunification.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the Chinese government values its economic and trade
cooperation with Benin. During the last 25 years, the two
countries have developed various and effective cooperation in
these areas on the basis of equality and mutual benefits.
</P>
<P>
Although China's assistance to Benin is limited in amount, its
help is sincere and unselfish, Jiang said, adding that China is
willing to continue its assistance to Benin, and to actively probe
new areas and ways to develop bilateral cooperation based on
equality and mutual benefits.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side is ready to promote trade between Chinese
companies and Benin, and encourage Chinese companies to expand
imports from Benin, and visit Benin to discuss joint equity or
cooperation between the two nation's businesses, Jiang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presidents of China, Benin Hold Talks in Beijing (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang said that China respects the political system and way of
development chosen by the Benin people according to the national
conditions of their country, supports Benin's efforts to maintain
its national unity, enhance its economy and improve the livelihood
of its people.
</P>
<P>
Kerekou briefed Jiang on Benin's views on the situation in
Africa and in the world and the latter also briefed the Benin
president on China's policy toward Africa.
</P>
<P>
China attaches importance to Africa and to establish friendly,
equal, mutually beneficial and cooperative relations with African
countries is an important part of China's independent foreign
policy of peace, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is ready to work together with African
countries to foster a long-term, stable and cooperative
state-to-state relationship oriented toward the 21st century,
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
China is also ready to make contributions to the establishment
of a peaceful, stable, fair and rational international political
and economic order along with the rest of the world, he added.
</P>
<P>
Following the talks, the two presidents attended the signing
ceremony of a number of bilateral trade, economic and
technological cooperation agreements, including one in which the
Chinese government will provide an interest-free loan to the Benin
government.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Jiang presided over a welcome ceremony in
honor of his Benin counterpart.  
</P>
</TEXT>
