<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most S. Koreans Prefer Wage Cuts to Mass Layoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Six out of every 10 South Koreans
would like to share the country's current hardships through wage
cuts instead of mass layoffs, said a survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by Hyundai Research Institute among 500
adults across the nation, showed that 63 percent of those surveyed
said they or their families feared losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
To survive the economic restructuring set by the International
Monetary Fund as a condition for the rescue loans of 57 billion
U.S. dollars, 68 percent said they preferred sharing pains through
cutting labor hours and wages.
</P>
<P>
Forty-three percent said they were willing to endure a 10
percent wage cut if it would help avoid large-scale layoffs.
</P>
<P>
Once the 11th largest economy in the world, the country has
been in serious financial crisis since the late 1997. It was
triggered by the failure of conglomerates and bad loans of
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The per capita productivity in the nation has dropped to 9,400
U.S. dollars from the previous year's 10,548 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK Voter Registration Ends with Good Results (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A two-month-odd registration
drive for the Hong Kong Legislative Council election concluded
with a total of 2.77 million eligible people registered in
geographical constituencies.
</P>
<P>
This represented a registration rate of nearly 70 percent of
3.96 million eligible electors in Hong Kong and an increase of
240,000 compared with the figure in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In addition, half of an estimate of 230,000 eligible people in
Functional constituencies have also registered.
</P>
<P>
Justice Woo Kwok-hing, chairman of the Electoral Affairs
Commission, expressed the satisfaction with the final result,
saying that he was quite happy about it.
</P>
<P>
The smooth voter registration is believed to be a result of
common efforts by both the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) and Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
It is known to all that the May Legislative Council election,
the first of its kind since Hong Kong returned to China last July,
is regarded as one of the important steps for the Hong Kong people
to govern Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the election is to produce a Legislative
Council which is credible and representative. The 60-member
legislature will be made up of 20 to be returned from the
geographical constituencies through direct election, 30 by
functional constituencies and 10 by an 800-member Election
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government is committed to ensuring that the
arrangements for the election are fair, open and honest and is
acceptable to the people of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the government has attached great importance to
the voter registration drive from November 5 last year to January
16 this year and spared no efforts to make it convenient for
every eligible resident to exercise their civil rights.
</P>
<P>
Posters bearing "Hong Kong is our home" and "Let's create our
future together" both in Chinese and English were specially
designed for the election registration and could be seen on walls
of major office and residential buildings during the registration
period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK Voter Registration Ends with Good Results (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Home Affairs Department set up counters at MTR stations and
bus termini to help people register.
</P>
<P>
A total of 30,000 voter registration ambassadors, who are
mostly teenage students, walked out to knock doors of every family
throughout Hong Kong in early December to help those who are Hong
Kong permanent residents and are 18 years old or above sign up as
electors for the Legislative Council election.
</P>
<P>
As a result, they visited nearly two million households during
the voter registration week from December 6 to 12.
</P>
<P>
"This is indeed a very impressive record. Every household has
been given the opportunity and convenience at their doorstep to
sign up as electors," Woo said.
</P>
<P>
The Registration and Electoral Office also had a series of
briefings for major organizations to explain the registration
process and made thousands of telephone calls to urge all eligible
people in functional constituencies to register.
</P>
<P>
In addition, David Lan Hong-tsun, secretary for Home Affairs,
visited a center for the elderly to help senior citizens to
complete the registration form. Other officials also went to
hospitals, universities and some other organizations to help
people get registered.
</P>
<P>
The concerted efforts of the government and people have brought
about a good beginning for the Legislative Council election.
However, much work still remains to be done.
</P>
<P>
The Registration and Electoral Office is now working flat out
to process the data collected from new applicants and previously
registered electors.
</P>
<P>
The revised guidelines on election-related activities for the
Legislative Council general election on May 24 and the Election
Committee subsector election in April are expected to be published
in February based on wide-ranging public consultations.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the objectives set by the government will
be surely realized so long as the principle of Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong is fully implemented.  
</P>
</TEXT>
