<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Determined to Recruit All Civil Servants Through Open Exams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The system of recruiting new
civil servants through open exams is now practiced in all
departments of China's central government, as well as every
provincial government across the country, an official with the
Ministry of Personnel said here today.
</P>
<P>
Since the State Council issued the Provisional Regulations on
Civil Servants in 1993, the Chinese central government has
organized nine major exams to recruit nearly 3,000 civil servants
from over 40,000 candidates, said Liu Jialin, director of the Exam
and Recruitment Department under the Personnel Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"To date, all departments under the State Council, except four
which have no vacancy, have adopted the exam system in their
recruitment," he said, adding that provincial governments of the
31 provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities across China
have all followed suit.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, governments at the provincial, prefectural,
county and township levels in 18 provinces even held unified exams
to recruit new blood. A total of 520,000 people competed for the
53,000 offered positions.
</P>
<P>
"Among all these newly-recruited civil servants, 2,636 used to
be farmers, and 664 used not to be residents of the places where
they are now serving as public servants," he noted.
</P>
<P>
At a recent conference in Beijing, Dai Guangqian, vice minister
of personnel, pointed out that at present, most Chinese people
know that anyone who wants to be civil servants can participate in
and must pass the open exam of recruitment.
</P>
<P>
"This should be regarded as a major step forward in China's
reform of personnel system and adoption of the civil service
system," he commented.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that due to the upcoming government streamlining,
which was decided during the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China last September, it would be impossible
for the central government bodies to enroll too many people this
year.
</P>
<P>
"But we should by no means lower our standards on choosing the
people, and the principle of basing all recruitments on open exams
would never be abandoned or changed," he vowed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,722 people Killed by Fires in 1997 in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A total of 2,722 people were
killed by more than 140,000 major fires last year in China,
causing a total property loss of 1.54 billion yuan (193 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The fires also injured 4,930, according to a senior official
with the Ministry of Public Security.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, 5,600 people were rescued and 168.5
billion yuan worth of property was saved because of the efforts of
relevant departments, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The number of fires was increasing, but there were fewer
conflagrations which caused great human and property losses, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the fires were attributed to inadequate safety
precautions in buildings, a lack of fire-control systems and
public fire-prevention facilities, and inadequate awareness of the
danger of fires among the general public, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: British Man to Bicycle Along Yellow River (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A British man is going to
travel along the 5,464-km Yellow River on a bicycle and write a
book afterwards.
</P>
<P>
This would be his second such long march after he covered the
1,782-km Grand Canal, one of the world's longest and oldest
canals, and all the way southward to Guangzhou and Hong Kong in
late 1995 and wrote an English book "China's Imperial Way --
Retracing A Historical Trade &AMP; Communications Route From Beijing
to Hong Kong".
</P>
<P>
Kevin Bishop, who's been residing in Hong Kong for ten years,
stayed in Beijing for two weeks and met with dozens of
geographers, travelers and officials, as part of his preparation
for the trip.
</P>
<P>
Only able to make simple and superfacial conversations in
Chinese, the 190-cm-tall man is also looking around for an
English-speaking Chinese assistant to cycle with him along the
river. The man will also be responsible for making research on the
Yellow River and arranging interviews for him with local people.
</P>
<P>
Bishop, told Xinhua in a recent snowy day that he is also
contacting some big companies who work along the Yellow River for
sponsors. Because the proceeds of Yellow River book will go to a
charity, the Orbis, whose flying eye hospital is active in China,
he hopes that some companies will like his idea and regard their
contribution as worthwhile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Champion Makinen out of Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- World champion Tommi Makinen
abandoned the Monte Carlo rally after skidding off the road during
the first stage of the second leg on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Finn, who led by more than a minute after the first leg on
Monday, lost control of his Mitsubshi Lancer in sub-zero
temperatures and went off the road.
</P>
<P>
Spaniard Carlos Sainz won the stage by 12 seconds in his Toyota
Corolla and became the current overall leader.
</P>
<P>
Juha Kankkunen of Finland in a Ford Escort came as second and
Belgian Bruno Thiry, also in Ford Escort, was third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
