<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Village Mayor Vows Tight Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Japan pledged tight security in
next month's Nagano Winter Olympics as they unveiled the
newly-built Olympic Village to the media on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Village Mayor Shozo Sasahara told a news conference that they
have put security to the top of their agenda in order to guard
against any attacks during the two-week Winter Games opening on
February 7.
</P>
<P>
The village, seven kilometers south of central Nagano and home
to some 3,000 competitors and officials during the Games, has
adopted tight security system.
</P>
<P>
All those entering the village, including the mayor, are
required to pass through metal detectors at two security gates.
</P>
<P>
A total of 6,000 police in the city will be mobilized during
the Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
