<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Substantial Progress in Sino-U.S. Strategic Ties (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's first snow of the new
year in mid-January ushered in the first U.S. cabinet member --
Defense Secretary William Cohen, which indicates a good beginning
for the Sino-U.S. strategic dialogue in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Local media agreed that Cohen, who led a 57-member delegation
on an official visit here Jan. 17-20, represents another
high-level contact between the two countries since President Jiang
Zemin's successful state visit to the United States in October
last year and the continuation of Sino-U.S. strategic dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The media noted that the ties between the two states and the
two armies have been further improved and are more mature, and
substantial progress has been made.
</P>
<P>
Cohen's just-ended visit is another step of a substantial
nature for the two countries toward establishing a constructive
strategic partnership oriented toward the 21st century, and should
serve to lay a solid foundation for this year's visit to China by
U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after his arrival, Cohen was warmly received and
honored with high courtesy and his achievements were obvious in
his 68-hour stay in Beijing: meetings with Jiang and Vice-Premier
Qian Qichen, and talks and meetings with senior Chinese military
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also visited military facilities in Beijing and was the
first U.S. secretary of defense to speak at the Academy of
Military Science of the People's Liberation Army. He signed an
agreement establishing a consultation mechanism to strengthen
maritime military safety.
</P>
<P>
Cohen and his Chinese hosts exchanged views "in a frank way" on
international and regional situations, bilateral relations and
other issues of shared concern.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told Cohen during their meeting that both sides regarded
his October visit to the United States as a complete
success. Jiang said he welcomes Clinton's upcoming visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, commenting on military ties, said in the past year that
contacts between the two armies have been active and that both
sides had fruitful talks during Cohen's current visit. He said he
hoped the new year would see greater progress in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Qian, also foreign minister of China, said leaders of the two
nations have set a goal of making concerted efforts toward the
establishment of a Sino-U.S. constructive strategic partnership.
</P>
<P>
Describing the current Sino-U.S. ties as good, Qian said this
relationship is now faced with new opportunities and the ties
between the two armies should lead to even greater progress
following the improvement of state ties.
</P>
<P>
As for the Chinese military sector, Qian said that in the past
year military ties have gained momentum and now enter into a new
period of advancement in which Cohen's visit signals a good
beginning.
</P>
<P>
The military leaders stressed that the signing of the agreement
on a military consultation mechanism indicates the army ties have
made substantial progress, which is conducive to peace and
stability in Asia and the Pacific, and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will serve to enhance mutual understanding, trust
and cooperation, a concrete indication of the positive efforts of
both sides for peace and stability, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
China has made positive efforts to safeguard world and regional
peace and stability, Qian said, and its ties with all powers
within the region have improved, while good neighbor ties have
been enhanced.
</P>
<P>
Facts have proved that China has become an important yet
positive factor to promote peace, stability and prosperity in
Asia, the Pacific and the world, Qian said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Substantial Progress in Sino-U.S. Strategic Ties (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, there have been problems in Sino-U.S. ties, the most
important and most sensitive of which is the Taiwan issue. If this
can be handled well, bilateral ties are expected to advance.
Otherwise, there could be some rough spots in the relationship.
</P>
<P>
On a series of occasions, Cohen stressed that it is very
important for the United States to develop ties with China, as
both countries are powers with great influence as well as
permanent members of the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Both nations will try to strengthen consultations and
cooperation, and jointly promote stability and prosperity in Asia,
the Pacific and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that the United States attaches great importance to
its ties with China, as this is in the interests and aspirations
of the people of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the U.S. government will adhere to the "one
China" policy, observe the three joint communiques signed by the
two nations, and continue its "engagement policy" toward China, as
it deems the last U.S.-China summit has been successful and the
bilateral constructive strategic partnership is moving ahead.
</P>
<P>
Although differences still exist on the issues of Taiwan and
human rights, a framework has been guiding bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
As an important part of the state-to-state relationship,
military ties have already had a good beginning, according to the
consensus reached between Jiang and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said contacts between the two armies have reached an
unprecedented level in the past year, saying this is not only in
the interests of the two nations, but also beneficial to peace and
stability in Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The United States hopes high-level and professional contacts
continue, cooperation be reinforced and new ways of cooperation be
explored, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
The defense secretary said the document on a military mechanism
has reflected the army ties as mature and that this is conducive
to improve and strengthen the understanding, communication and
contacts between the two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Local observers point out that Cohen's visit opened the curtain
of U.S. "Asia Diplomacy" this year, which would serve to deepen,
broaden and promote the strategic dialogue between China and the
United States, and push the improved state ties and the
increasingly mature military ties to a new period of progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
