<HEADLINE> Government Recruits 2,000 Civil Servants from College Graduates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- China has recruited 2,000 civil
servants from college graduates for the departments of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China and the central
government.
</P>
<P>
The two examinations, held at the first half and the end of
last year, were expected to bring in more than 2,000 employees for
the departments and ministries of the central government,
according to the Ministry of Personnel.
</P>
<P>
The first exam was held in Beijing, Shanghai, Xi'an and
Shenyang to recruit 1,048 employees for 86 government agencies,
and a total of 8,118 people took the examination, said Liu Jialin,
director of the ministry's exam and recruitment department.
</P>
<P>
He added that the second exam was held in the eight cities of
Beijing, Shanghai, Shenyang, Xi'an, Wuhan, Nanjing, Chengdu and
Guangzhou on December 6.
</P>
<P>
About 23,000 college students to be graduate in the summer of
1998 sat in the exam and 966 of them have been picked by 84
central departments, said Liu.
</P>
<P>
"The recruitment of civil servants from graduating students
provide an open and fair chance of competition for the students,"
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The ministry started the examination system in 1995, and has so
far recruited more than 1,500 college graduates, most of whom are
reportedly handle their work well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
