<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: HK Remains World's Busiest Container Port (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is expected to beat
all the other rivals to rank as the world's busiest container port
for the sixth year in a row in 1997, Richard Yuen, deputy
secretary for economic services, said.
</P>
<P>
The total container throughput is projected to reach 14.5
million Twenty-Foot Equivalent Units (TEUs), up 8.5 percent from
the previous year, Yuen said in a recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the container traffic is handled by the eight
existing container terminals located at Kwai Chung, which have
been built and operated by the private sector. Hong Kong is the
world's only major port that does not have a port authority.
</P>
<P>
The remaining container traffic is handled mid-stream, or by
river trade, taking advantage of the waterway of the Pearl River.
</P>
<P>
"The great achievement in 1997 should be attributed to the
double-digit increase in the export of South China and the
continued healthy economic performance of the United States," Yuen
observed.
</P>
<P>
The importance of China's inland areas, particularly South
China, to Hong Kong can never be overvalued, said Yuen, who is
also secretary for the Port Development Board which advises the
government on port development.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has been serving far beyond itself to be the leading
port in South China," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Cargo throughput of a port is a key barometer of the economic
and trade development of a country or a region, Yuen noted.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, winning the title of the world's busiest
container port is an indication of the enviable economic growth in
China.
</P>
<P>
Yuen believes that so long as China maintains a sustained
economic growth, Hong Kong will surely enjoy a steady increase in
container throughput well into the next century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: HK Remains World's Busiest Container Port (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to the motherland on July 1, 1997, the
port's leading position has been further enhanced thanks to the
"one country, two systems" principle, Yuen said.
</P>
<P>
"One country" facilitates exchanges and coordination between
the two economically integrated sides while "two systems"
preserves all the factors contributing to Hong Kong's past
success, including free economy, free port and high efficiency,
Yuen pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Port Development Board has been in frequent contact with
the port authorities of neighboring Shenzhen city and China's
Ministry of Communications. Yuen himself has visited nearly all
the ports along China's winding coastline, from Shenzhen's Shekou
and Yantian northward to Dalian.
</P>
<P>
One of his board's major jobs is to compile medium- and
long-term port cargo forecasts by examining economic and trade
development, containerization trends and potential competition
from other ports. The forecasts serve as the basis of the
government's port development program and are revised every two
years.
</P>
<P>
The latest forecasts, published in 1996, projected an annual
growth rate of 5.9 percent in container throughput through to the
year 2016 when the port is expected to handle 3.9 million TEUs, or
five TEUs every four seconds. The next forecasts will be published
early this year.
</P>
<P>
To cope with demand, construction of a ninth container terminal
on Tsing Yi Island, opposite the container port at Kwai Chung,
will start soon. Moreover, a new container port is being planned
for Lantau Island and next to the new airport.
</P>
<P>
As a large share of cargo passing through Hong Kong is
entreport trade with South China, the waterway of the Pearl River
is being increasingly used. Work on the construction of Hong
Kong's first river trade terminal (RTT) is now under way near Tuen
Mun in the northwestern part of the "New Territories." The first
phase of the RTT is due to begin operation in 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
