<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Urges Austerity in ASEAN Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines, which currently
chairs the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), has
called for austerity measures in the conduct of ASEAN meetings and
related activities, the Philippine News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Foreign Affairs said it has submitted a set
of proposals to the ASEAN Secretary General in Jakarta, Rodolfo
Severino, intended to cut costs of ASEAN meetings.
</P>
<P>
The four-point proposal the Philippines submitted includes the
following:
</P>
<P>
-- Maximizing the participation of embassies in ASEAN meetings
with the secretariat scheduling various meetings early to enable
embassies to prepare for such meetings;
</P>
<P>
-- Holding meetings in ASEAN capitals only if such meetings
should be outside the secretariat in Jakarta to avoid connecting
flights for delegates;
</P>
<P>
-- Shortening duration of meetings by having more informal
working dinners or lunches and limiting the reading of formal
statements to reduce hosting costs; and
</P>
<P>
-- Reviewing documentation practices to reduce paper and
duplication costs, and adopting a document coding system for their
efficient classification and retrieval.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine proposal, initiated in reaction to the current
economic difficulties resulting from the currency crisis sweeping
the ASEAN region, will be taken up during the second meeting of
the 31st ASEAN Standing Committee in Jakarta from February 10 to
12.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta meeting, the report added, will also consider the
matter of reducing ASEAN meetings by resorting to ad-referendum on
certain matters as may be agreed upon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Continous Anti-Corruption Vital to Success in 1998: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Continuous anti-corruption is
vital to smooth accomplishment of all the tasks for 1998, a senior
Chinese official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the second session of the Central Commission of
Discipline Inspection of the Communist Party of China (CPC), which
opened today in Beijing, Wei Jianxing, Standing Committee member
of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee, said
greater efforts must be made to build an honest and clean
government in accordance with the guidelines set forth at the 15th
National Party Congress in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
Wei, also secretary of the commission, said 1998 is the first
year for an overall fulfilment of the tasks set out at the 15th
Party Congress and therefore, continuous anti-corruption this year
is vital to accomplish all the tasks.
</P>
<P>
He called on Party committees and discipline inspection
commissions at various levels to adhere more firmly and
consciously to the guidelines drawn by the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
He asked them to proceed from China's actual situation of the
primary stage of socialism, be well aware of the importance of
anti-corruption in the reform, opening-up and modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping Theory should be the guidance for all the work
relating to Party building and anti-corruption in 1998, Wei
reiterated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
