<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Telecom Agrees to Early Terminate Exclusive Licence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Telecom
International Limited (HKTI) has agreed to the termination of its
exclusive international licence on March 31 before its schedule
expiry in October 2006.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed between Stephen Ip, Secretary for
Economic Services, and Linus Cheung, chief executive of the Hong
Kong Telecom International here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The HKTI currently holds an exclusive licence to provide
external telecommunications services and circuits, including
international direct dial (IDD) voice telephony services. Its
exclusive licence was issued in 1981 and was due to expire in
2006.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the government will seek from the Finance
Committee of the Provisional Legislative Council a sum of 6.7
billion Hong Kong dollars (858.97 million U.S. dollars) as
compensation to the HKTI early termination of its exclusive
rights.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government will also waive all royalty by the
HKTI as from Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ip hailed the agreement as another major breakthrough in the
development of telecommunications in Hong Kong, adding: "before
this agreement, our external telecommunications sector was out of
line with the best current international practice and this has had
adverse implications for our regional competitiveness in
telecommunications."
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased that we are able to remove this remaining anomaly
in our otherwise fully liberalized telecommunications market,
thereby furthering our policy objective of maintaining Hong Kong
as the pre-eminent telecommunications hub in the Asian Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
"This liberalization coming at this time of economic
uncertainty in the region will also give Hong Kong a significant
economic stimulus," Ip said.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang welcomed this agreement as a
major step in enhancing Hong Kong's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
"Telecommunications plays a vital role in underpinning the
service sector which contributes to more than 83 percent of our
Gross Domestic Product and enhancing our competitiveness against
other economies in the region and in the world.
</P>
<P>
"This is particularly so as we enter the Information Age where
the efficient flow and effective utilization of information will
be a key to the competitiveness of an economy," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
Cheung said: "this agreement balances the interests of all
stakeholders and provides fair compensation to Hong Kong Telecom
for giving up a valuable asset."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
