<HEADLINE> British Official Calls for Fresh Start in Britain-China Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Just before leaving for Hong
Kong, visiting British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said at a news
conference here today that there will be a "fresh start" in
relations between Great Britain and China.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that he has held "positive and friendly" meetings
with Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen, and both sides want bilateral relations to
have a "fresh start down a broad road, which is wide enough for us
to develop relations on the many matters of common interest to us
both."
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries have a common interest in the
successful solution of the Hong Kong question, and the principle
of "one country, two systems" is working well.
</P>
<P>
Britain and China also have a common interest in international
issues as permanent members of the United Nations Security
Council, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that Britain is the second largest European
trading partner with China and an important European investor and
supplier of new technology to China, adding that bilateral trade
of mutual benefit should be further strengthened.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that during the second Asia-Europe Meeting
scheduled for April in London, Great Britain, which is to chair
the European Union, will hold the first-ever European Union-China
Summit. And this will recognize China's growing importance, both
economic and diplomatic, on the world stage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
