<HEADLINE> Roundup: China to Train More Enterprise Administrators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Experts say that China will
need at least 100,000 licensed accountants, 200,000 masters of
business administration (MBA), as well as one million enterprise
executives with proper training in business administration to
fulfill the goal for advancing market economy and expanding
enterprise reform.
</P>
<P>
Based on this prediction, more than one million on-job workers
and reserve working force in China's state-owned enterprises will
have to be trained in the coming years. Therefore, training
enterprise administrative personnel has become an urgent matter.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the State Commission for Economy and Trade say
that training administrative personnel for enterprises will be
focused on improving these people's structure of knowledge and the
capacity to understand the market.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports show that some 100,000 administrative workers
of different enterprises in China have participated in various
kinds of training courses on business administration, including
19,000 managing executives of large and medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The State Commission for Economy and Trade have jointly
started an advanced training courses to enterprises leaders.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's governing body, has also offered 19
training courses to administrative personnel from the country's
large state-owned enterprises, and Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo
delivered speeches to the trainees on two occasions.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the country's major universities offer MBA
courses and short-term training courses to enterprise
administrative workers.
</P>
<P>
China has also cooperated with foreign countries in training
more enterprise administrative personnel.
</P>
<P>
China and Britain have been implementing a five-year
comprehensive training plan under which, China sends selected
enterprise administrative personnel and technological workers to
Britain to receive training or study for diplomas beginning from
1997, while the British side will send experts to China to give
consultation on enterprise management.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts believe that China's decisions to adjust and
improve ownership structure of the state-owned enterprises, making
it necessary to train more administrative personnel.
</P>
<P>
They predict that the training of enterprise administrative
workers will be carried out extensively in China in the future and
will become a new hot topic for China's economic reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
