<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pakistan's Economy Still Full of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The much expected economic
recovery in Pakistan is still uncertain as the performance of the
major economic sectors during the first half of the current fiscal
year turned out to be unsatisfactory.
</P>
<P>
A six-month economic review reveals the recession is still
plaguing. The vital industrial sector has not picked up as desired
and the expected growth rate of this sector could hardly be
achieved in the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the review of economic performance for the first six
months (July-December) of 1997-98 last weekend, Finance Minister
Sartaj Aziz admitted that the reform packages announced by the
current government this year could not produce the desired
results.
</P>
<P>
He said the economic growth rate as projected in the last
budget at six percent would be difficult to achieve in the face of
shortfall in the production of cotton and the slower than expected
performance of the industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
However, he was confident that the growth rate might range
between 5.2 and 5.5 percent which would conform to the targets as
set forth in the agreement with the International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
One worrying thing in the half-year economic review is the
lower than expected tax revenue. Figures contained in the review
show that the Central Board of Revenue (CBR) was facing a
shortfall of at least 10 percent during the first half of 1997-98
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
After managing to collect about 41 percent, or 135 billion
rupees (about 3.1 billion U.S. dollars) during the first six
months of the current fiscal year, the CBR is facing an uphill
task to generate 59 percent, or 189 billion rupees (4.3 billion
dollars) during the remaining half.
</P>
<P>
The revenue target for the current fiscal year is 324 billion
rupees (7.4 billion dollars) based on the assumption of a 14
percent growth over the preceding year's 282 billion rupees (6.4
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, during the first half of 1997-98, tax revenue showed a
negative growth of about one percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, public sector corporations are still in heavy
losses, exacerbating the government's already fragile financial
position, though so far the government's bank borrowing has been
contained in the budget limit.
</P>
<P>
One major positive thing in the half-year economic performance
was that the external balance improved by 1.6 billion dollars.
However, it was mainly due to transitory factors. Export growth
remained low at eight percent against the 15 percent target.
</P>
<P>
Most worrisome is the industrial sector decline. Industrial
growth of a nominal one percent obviously made the target of seven
percent hard to be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Local economists are of the view that the overall growth in the
economy will be lower than the six percent target set for this
fiscal year. Given the poor cotton crop and the industrial slump,
the growth rate of around 5.5 percent as projected by the
government also seems hard to achieve.
</P>
<P>
While a bumper crop of sugarcane at 51 million tons shows an
increase of four percent, rice will grow by more than four
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, cotton crop, which is the backbone of Pakistan's
economy, is pretty weak this year. The crop, hit by rains causing
a loss of one million bales, is expected be less than last year's
9.4 million bales.
</P>
<P>
Following the worst manufacturing year which recorded a
negative growth of 1.45 percent, the sector recorded growth of one
percent during the five months ending last November in the current
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The output, however, improved by 5.1 percent in November,
possibly because of the 8.7 percent devaluation of the Pak
currency in October which made exports cheaper.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's large scale manufacturing sector has been the
weakest in the economy for the last five years when the
performance was far below five percent while the target of growth
rate was seven to eight percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that higher industrial growth is the key
to larger revenues, more exports, particularly the value-added,
higher employment, better stock market prices and better repayment
of loans.
</P>
<P>
But because of the poor industrial growth there have been
setbacks all round in the economy despite the various incentives
announced by the government, including tax relief.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the benefits of the reform packages
initiated by the present government since it came to power in
February last year could not materialize over these months because
of the domestic political crisis and the financial crisis in East
Asia.
</P>
<P>
It is by any means encouraging for Pakistan's economy that the
country has come out without any serious damage from the recent
financial crisis in East Asia, though the four-month-long domestic
political crisis has undoubtedly slowed down recovery process and
adversely affected exports.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the overall investment climate has remained
within manageable limits despite all those negative factors.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that as the financial crisis in East Asia is
subsiding and political stability in the country has been
restored, better economic results should emerge.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
