<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Explains Policy on S. Leone, Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The April 22 deadline for Sierra
Leone's military junta to quit remains despite hiccups in the
planned disarmament of conflicting parties, the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) has announced.
</P>
<P>
But the sub-regional body seeks a compromise with Liberian
President Charles Taylor in the row over the role of the ECOWAS
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG, the Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing Monday at the Nigerian capital of Abuja,
ECOWAS Executive Secretary Lansana Kouyate said there was no
going back on the date set for the junta to restore President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, who was ousted in a coup on May 25 last year.
</P>
<P>
The junta, which signed a peace accord last October agreeing
to hand over power on the set date, threatened later to postpone
the end of the peace process due to delay in disarmament and
delivery of international relief goods.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS scribe was also optimistic that a disagreement
between ECOWAS and the United Nations on troops deployment to
Sierra Leone will be amicably resolved.
</P>
<P>
According to former ECOMOG force Commander Maj.-Gen. Victor
Malu, about 15,000 troops will be needed for the Sierra Leone
assignment.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the logistics, Kouyate said "the UN wants ECOMOG to
deploy into Sierra Leone first, but we are disagreeing. We think
they should land there before us."
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS Committee of Five on Sierra Leone, which is
expected to meet early next month on the disagreement, "needs
concrete deeds to make deployment to Sierra Leone possible," he
added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, consultations between ECOWAS and UN on all
fronts are currently underway.
</P>
<P>
"The UN has practically endorsed all the decisions we have
taken. But we are eagerly awaiting their observer mission."
</P>
<P>
A UN fact-finding team, led by the organization's special
envoy to Sierra Leone, paid a three-day visit to the tiny west
African country last week to pave the way for the observers.
</P>
</TEXT>
