<HEADLINE> S. African Ex-President to Be Given Even-handed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The South African
magistrate set to try former state president P W Botha promised
Monday that he would give an even-handed trial to the man who
ruled the country in height of the Apartheit years.
</P>
<P>
Victor Lugaju, the president of the Western Cape Regional
Court, said he would treat the matter "like any other case", the
Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We dispense justice to all persons in the same way. We do not
differentiate," said Lugaju, who will preside over the court
hearing Friday on Botha's failure to appear before the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC).
</P>
<P>
Botha, who had defied a third subpoena from the TRC last
December to testify for hearings of the former State Security
Council, was served with a summon from Western Cape
Attorney-General Frank Kahn earlier this month to appear in
George Regional Court on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lugaju, 49, said he wanted to show that the "justice system is
real in South Africa".
</P>
<P>
He said that he chose to take the case himself as the top
magistrate in the Western Cape province, when other magistrates
had full schedules.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing the idea that he had any personal desire to handle
the case, Lugaju said: "I can take any case. There is nothing
special about it."
</P>
<P>
Botha, 81, faces a two-year imprisonment and/or fines if
convicted. But observers said that a fine is more likely due to
his age and physical ailments.
</P>
<P>
During his 11 years in power, including the prime minister
office between 1978 and 1984 and later as state president until
1989, Botha enacted emergency laws to crack down on
anti-apartheid groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
