<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Resume Pharmaceutical Export to Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is expected to soon
resume export of its pharmaceutical products to Ghana after
nearly four years of suspension ordered by the Ghanaian
government.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made by the Ghana Food and Drugs Board (GFDB)
which ended a week-long fact-finding visit to Nigeria last
weekend, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ghana clamped a ban in early 1994 on importation of
pharmaceutical products from west African countries, including
Nigeria, in the wake of rampant circulation of fake and spurious
drugs in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
According to GFDB Chief Executive Theophilus Corquaye, the
suspension order will soon be lifted to enable Nigeria to resume
exportation of the commodities.
</P>
<P>
Noting that drug manufacturing facilities in Nigeria compared
favorably with those in advanced countries in the world, Corquaye
said, his team would evaluate its findings and make
recommendations to the Ghanaian government accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Corquaye, leader of the five-member team, said the structures
already in place for the trade in drugs had to be addressed
before importation could resume.
</P>
<P>
The export is expected to increase the capacity utilization of
Nigerian manufacturing companies by 20 percent, according to
reports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigerian pharmaceutical manufacturers are preparing
to hold a symposium-exhibition of Nigeria-made drugs in Ghana as
soon as the permission for formal export of local pharmaceuticals
is granted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
