<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Economy Remains Stagnant, Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Japan's economy still remains at
a standstill, the Bank of Japan (BOJ) said Tuesday in its monthly
report.
</P>
<P>
"The positive growth cycle of production, income and
expenditures has stalled," the central bank said, adding that
sluggish domestic demand, especially in the area of household
expenditures, has hurt production, employment and income.
</P>
<P>
Net exports have continued to increase, and business investment
has risen moderately -- primarily in the manufacturing sector,
said the report, which covered this month's financial and economic
developments.
</P>
<P>
Poor demand helped spread inventory adjustment pressures and
industrial production has slightly declined, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The BOJ external demand is expected to continue to support
economic growth, and special tax-cut measures announced in
December 1997 could help household spending.
</P>
<P>
Despite this, the overall economy is likely to remain stagnant
for a while and to be vulnerable to further negative impacts, the
bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
