<HEADLINE> Share Prices Decline on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Share prices drifted lower on
the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index declined by 30.27 points to close at 1296.91 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said stocks were spooked by uncertainties in regional
currencies and eroding confidence that Asia would soon start
pulling out of its economic crisis. They said that selling
continued even after Singapore's non-oil domestic exports for
December last year showed a robust 13.3 percent increase
year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume stood at 361.11 million units, valued at
462.54 million Singapore dollars (about 262.81 million U.S.
dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 293 to 91, while 226
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
MBf Capital was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 17.99 million units. It was followed by
Renong Bhd which had 15.23 million shares traded. Rekapac was next
with 14.7 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Elec led the gainers of the day as it rose by 75 cents to
finish at six U.S. dollars. Roth S. increased by 60 cents to end
at 8.5 Singapore dollars, while Creative 50 was up by 40 cents to
close at 33.5 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, NBT was the biggest loser as it declined by
1.04 dollars to end at 4.56 Singapore dollars. DBS (Development
Bank of Singapore) Foreign fell by 60 cents to close at 11.8
Singapore dollars. And the OCBC (Overseas Chinese Banking
Corporation) Foreign dropped by 55 cents to finish at 7.7
Singapore dollars.  
</P>
