<HEADLINE> Kenyan Experts Assess Locust Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan crop protection experts
have been rushed to parts of Central Province following reports
of a locusts invasion into the region, the Daily Nation reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Among areas reportedly threatened by the devastating insects
include Murang'a and Maragua districts in Central Province and
Turkana in the arid north of the country, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The daily paper quoted a source in the Agriculture Ministry of
Kenya as saying that the teams of experts were dispatched as part
of the government response to the locust threat.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan police last week warned of a major locust invasion from
neighbouring Ethiopia where the locusts have been breeding for
several months.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Police Commissioner Geoffrey Mwathe said that he had
confirmed with his Ethiopian counterpart reports of locusts along
the Kenya-Ethiopia border this month.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said that locusts had been breeding in Sudan,
Eritrea, Ethiopia and in the Red Sea belt, and the recent heavy
rains in the region favoured the insects' breeding in arid areas.
</P>
<P>
Three months ago, a Food and Agriculture Organization mission
warned that swarms of African migratory locusts had been reported
to be moving out of their traditional outbreak areas... to major
agricultural areas.
</P>
<P>
Desert locusts which are the most devastating species feed on
green vegetation and explosive outbreaks can wipe out food
harvests over large areas of Africa, the Middle East and Western
Asia with heartbreaking efficiency, said a statement issued by
the International Center for Insect Physiology and Ecology last
November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
