<HEADLINE> Nigeria Shuts Down 26 Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Nigeria
announced the closure of 26 sick banks and the start of their
liquidation process Monday, in a bid to sanitize the country's
banking system.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the liquidation are 13 commercial banks and 13
merchant banks, namely the Allied Bank of Nigeria, the Merchant
Bank of Africa Limited and others.
</P>
<P>
Deposits totalling 16.33 billion Naira (about 218 million U.S.
Dollars) are trapped in the distressed banks, where about 6,000
staff will lose their jobs, according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
While briefing the press in Abuja, the governor of the central
bank, Paul Ogwuma appealed to depositors to exercise patience,
promising that their deposits will be settled by the Nigeria
Deposit Insurance Corporation after due verification.
</P>
<P>
The liquidation of distressed banks will enhance restoration
of full viability and confidence in the banking industry, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The governor also announced that the closed banks have been
put under police protection to prevent the loss of any
properties. 
</P>
