<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blacks' History Not Taught in S. African Schools: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Nearly four years have
passed since South Africa abolished apartheid in 1994, but many
students studying in poorly resourced schools still have no
access to learn the history of blacks in the country.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Sowetan quoted unidentified sources as reporting
that for many South African students history of the country began
in 1652 when the first white settler, Jan van Riebeeck, arrived
at what is now Cape Town, the legislative capital of South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
During apartheid time, public school teachers did not teach
black history before the Van Riebeeck. Textbooks made no mention
of the anti-apartheid struggle.
</P>
<P>
Only a few years ago, teachers in black schools could be
banished for violating curriculum restrictions imposed by the
minority white government.
</P>
<P>
"If you stepped out of bounds, you were demoted, and if you
did it again, you were sent to the rural area. If you refused to
go, you lost your job," a history teacher recalled.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the first non-racial general elections in 1994,
which ended white minority rule, new edition of series of
textbooks about South African history involving blacks, whites
and colored people, have been available in bookstores.
</P>
<P>
However, the latest history books are far from popular. "The
old texts are still used, especially in poorly resourced
schools," because "many schools can't afford to buy new stuff,"
said Sue Krige, who teaches education at the University of the
Witwatersrand in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
In addition, several new history books were reportedly
available in South Africa, but only three of the country's nine
provinces have formally approved the new books for use in public
schools this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
