<HEADLINE> Ancient Kilns Unearthed in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
unearthed two celadon kilns dating back over 1,000 years in
central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
They note that the discovery represents the first ever
well-preserved kilns dating to the Five Dynasties Period (907-960).
</P>
<P>
The Chenjian Kilns, located in Hengnan County, were used to
produce the period's famous blue and white porcelain.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists also unearthed abundant historical relics over a
three month period, including bowls, plates, ink stones and blue
jars tinged with grey or yellow.
</P>
<P>
One kiln also yielded a number of porcelain boxes, cups and
pillows. Archeologists say the relics will provide valuable clues
for research into the development of ancient porcelain
production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
