<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Continue Effective Protection of Foreign IPR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to provide
effective protection for the intellectual property rights (IPR) of
foreign investors in China and other business partners, according
to a government spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"IPR protection is an international obligation," according to a
spokesman for the State Council's IPR Work Conference
Office. "China seriously abides by international conventions and
bilateral agreements on IPR, which China has joined or signed,
expands exchanges, and deals with IPR relations with other
countries based on the principle of mutual benefit", the spokesman
said here today.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that China is considering further steps to protect
IPR in areas such as human genes, genetic engineering and new
pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
He said China will include IPR protection in both state and
regional development plans and will make it part of its economic
system and scientific programs.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that China adopted a major policy on
strengthening IPR protection in 1994 and has since recorded
monumental progress in adhering to international norms.
</P>
<P>
Provinces and major cities across the nation have established
IPR conference offices, with some 20 forming IPR tribunals. In
addition, more than one million government workers are directly
participating in the drive.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, China has closed 53 illegal CD production
lines, and under high pressure some lines had to be removed
abroad. Therefore, customs departments should remain on full alert
to halt imports and exports of equipment and products involving
piracy.
</P>
<P>
Criminal punishment must be imposed for serious cases, and
violators must be apprehended, regardless of the circumstances,
according to spokesman. In addition, all Chinese officials above
the county level will receive training in IPR laws over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will also pay close attention to the
piracy of Chinese products on the international market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
