<HEADLINE> Soeharto Ready to Run for 7th Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
on Tuesday expressed his readiness to run for the president for
the 1998-2003 period.
</P>
<P>
"AL-HAJ Mohamad Soeharto is prepared to be renominated for
presidency in the upcoming general session of the People's
Consultative Assembly for the 1998-2003 term of office," General
Chairman of the ruling Functional Group (Golkar) Harmoko announced
at the Bina Graha Presidential Office here.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko, together with chief of the Indonesian Armed Forces
(ABRI) Gen. Feisal Tanjung and Minister for Home Affairs Yogie S.
Memed, called on President Soeharto at Bina Graha.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko further announced the criteria for choosing the next
vice president, which includes mastery of science and technology.
</P>
<P>
He noted that after the president suggested to Golkar last year
to reconsider his renomination, the party had to ask the opinion
of its members from the central executive board down to the
provincial chapters.
</P>
<P>
"All letters sent (by the provincial chapters) to the party's
central executive board only gave one name, AL-HAJ Mohamad
Soeharto," said Harmoko, who is also speaker of the House of
Representatives (DPR) and the People's Consultative Assembly
(MPR).
</P>
<P>
He said the majority of the people have expressed their
willingness to renominate the president for a seventh term.
</P>
<P>
On the criteria for choosing the next vice president, Harmoko
said the candidate must be able to maintain national unity, must
have a vision of the future and a strong sense of nationalism and
patriotism.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko also said that the nominee must have a vision on
science and technology, have deep knowledge of industry and its
usage, and be ready to assist the president in solving various
problems that may emerge in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, 76, has ruled the country for 31 years since 1967.
</P>
<P>
The 1,000 members of the MPR will convene in March to elect a
president and vice president and establish the state policy
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Golkar has won all six elections held under President Soeharto.
Last May in a landslide election victory, Golkar obtained 74.3
percent of the votes, a significant increase from the 68 percent
it won in 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
