<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 600 Ugandans Escape Rare Marine Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Over 600 Ugandans escaped
drowning in Lake Kyoga in a rare marine accident, The Monitor
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Wamukomwe Sud, one of the 13 floating islands in the lake in
central Uganda, has been divided into two parts and started
sinking on January 16 night when a heavy downpour hit the lake.
</P>
<P>
Kasisaki Nsibirwa, the former local council vice-councillor of
Kalungi sub-county, Nakasongola District, told the paper that
part of it was breaking away and removed from its usual place and
got submerged. Some residents and vendors visiting the Sud to
collect fish started to desert the floating island by canoes.
</P>
<P>
Some of the victims are still missing for the time being.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds escaped to the three other nearby Suds and the
neighbor mainland districts, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Suds are floating islands in the waters of Nile River system
consisting of rotten branches and soil and covered with
vegetation. An interesting fact is that there were no cholera
cases in these Suds when half of the districts of the country was
hit by the epidemic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
