<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Economic Crisis to Be focused at 2nd ASEM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The current economic
crisis in Asia is expected to take center stage at the Second
Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) to be held in London next April,
Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
With the introduction of the single European currency next
year, the currency depreciation and economic crisis in this region
were crucial, he told reporters after meeting an 11-member
European Union (EU) parliamentary delegation led by Gunter Rinsche
of Germany.
</P>
<P>
ASEM is a forum which groups 15 EU member countries, China,
Japan, South Korea and several ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
Badawi said that he took the opportunity to explain to the
visitors that ASEAN was united in tackling the economic woes and
the weakening of the region's currencies and in boosting
intra-trade among them.
</P>
<P>
"I told them that ASEAN is aware that the problems cannot be
resolved by the grouping alone as they have a global dimension and
linked to the world currency trading," Badawi said.
</P>
<P>
He said ASEAN would continue their close ties among member
countries to overcome economic problems.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. Indonesia, Malaysia,
Thailand and the Philippines have been badly hit by the economic
crisis resulted from the speculative attacks on their currencies
since last July.
</P>
<P>
Badawi said he told the EU delegation that corrective measures
taken by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to help the
badly-hit countries had not shown the desired results.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has only sought technical advice from the IMF to tide
over the problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
The EU delegation was happy with the strengthening of the local
unit -- the ringgit and hoped that it would be a pointer for a
better economic situation in future, Badawi said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
