<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's External Trade Up in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's total trade
expanded by 8.4 percent at current prices in December 1997 on a
three-month moving average basis, with exports and imports
increasing by 9.1 percent and 7.7 percent respectively, the
government Trade Development Board (TDB) said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the month, non-oil domestic exports grew by 11.1 percent
while re-exports registered a growth of 10.8 percent. Oil domestic
exports, however, declined by 9.6 percent, the TDB said.
</P>
<P>
It said that non-oil domestic exports increased by 11.1 percent
to reach 8.5 billion Singapore dollars (5.06 billion US dollars)
in December, while re-exports reached seven billion Singapore
dollars (4.17 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The increase in re-exports came mainly from shipments of
integrated circuits, computer parts and peripherals, disk drives,
and other products.
</P>
<P>
Domestic exports of oil were weak, the TDB said, adding that
this was probably affected by keen competition from regional
refineries. It declined by 9.6 percent due mainly to lower
shipments of oil to Hong Kong and Japan.
</P>
<P>
On a monthly basis, the TDB said non-oil domestic exports rose
by 13.3 percent in December 1997, as domestic exports of
integrated circuits and printed circuit boards assembled (PCBA)
continued to expand.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of disk drives, which accounted for 19 percent of the
non-oil domestic exports, slowed further, growing only marginally
by 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Re-exports increased by 12.8 percent on a monthly basis. The
TDB noted that while re-exports of electronic products to the
United States, European Union, and Hong Kong expanded strongly,
this was partially offset by the drop in re-exports to Malaysia,
Singapore's top re-export market, and Thailand of 6.3 percent and
28.5 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
As exports grew, imports increased in December, according to
the TDB figures. Non-oil imports expanded by 8.3 percent to reach
15.8 billion Singapore dollars (about 9.4 billion US dollars) in
the month.
</P>
<P>
Increases were recorded in imports of integrated circuits,
computer parts and peripherals, disk drives, parts of
semiconductors, parts of aircraft, cigarettes, parts of color
television sets and radios, printed circuits, capacitors, and
other products, the TDB said.
</P>
<P>
It also said, however, that there were declines in imports of
blank computer tapes and discs, and parts of video cassette
recorders (VCRs).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 08:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Exports to Asia Fall in 4th Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli exports to the Far
East shrank by 200 million dollars, or 20 percent, in the fourth
quarter last year, largely due to the economic crisis spreading
across Asia, The Jerusalem Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a report presented to the Knesset
(Parliament) by the Industry and Trade Ministry as saying that
Israel's exports to Far East last year declined by 1 percent to
3.644 billion dollars from 3.679 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Topping the list, food and agriculture exports fell by 22
percent last year, while diamond exports declined 12 percent, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset Economic Committee convened a meeting of trade
officials and Asian diplomats Monday to discuss Israeli-Asian
trade and economic relations in light of the Asian monetary
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Industry and Trade Ministry Director-General Dov Mishor told
the meeting that despite the International Monetary Fund speaks
of decreased growth in world trade during 1998, the Israeli
government is still predicting a 9 percent growth in exports to
Asia this year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Ambassador to Israel Ronarong Nopakun said he
expected Israeli defense industries to be heavily hit by the
ongoing economic crisis in Asia because some countries lack hard
currency to pay for the purchase of advanced weapons.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Manufacturers Association's Textiles Division head Yair
Rotlevy estimated that the Asian crisis could cause Israeli
industry to lose 1 billion dollars in total. He said, to South
Korea alone, Israeli exports could shrink by 260 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Korean bilateral trade topped 700 million dollars in
1996, and was expected to rise to 1 billion dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Industry and Trade Minister Natan Sharansky urged Israeli
companies not to lose faith in the Asian tigers. He said Israel
would not change policies toward Asia despite the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Trying to allay concerns of Israeli exporters, South Korean
Ambassador Eui Yong Chung also played down the long-term major
impact the Asian crisis might have on Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said, of Israel's 530 million dollar exports to South Korea
in the first 11 months of 1997, about 400 million dollars were
high-tech products exports. The remainder principally comprised
components destined for end products in South Korea and 15 million
dollars in diamonds.
</P>
<P>
"I don't see any major impact, rather it's a good time for
potential investors from Israel to look at expanding their
interests in the region," Chung said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
