<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Province Leads China in Tax Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 20 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province recorded industrial and commercial taxes of some 100
billion yuan in 1997, up 24.4 percent on 1996 and accounting for
14 percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
The province has focused its efforts on economic development
and cultivating new tax sources, especially in the area of major
infrastructure and pillar industries, according to Chen Liuming,
director of the provincial tax bureau.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the province had had 18 key enterprises
each contributing more than 100 million yuan in taxes annually and
232 others each contributing over 10 million yuan. Guangdong's
34,000 foreign-funded enterprises paid taxes totalling 16 billion
yuan and its 742,000 private businesses contributed an additional
5.88 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong's taxation departments strengthened efforts to battle
tax evasion and recovered 2.6 billion yuan in taxes during 1997
alone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
