<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Slightly Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
finished a lackluster day's trade slightly lower, marked by an
afternoon of thin trading with virtually no overseas direction.
</P>
<P>
Weaker resource stocks, impacted by lower metals prices
overnight, weighed on the market.
</P>
<P>
Nevitts broker Craig Wright said Tuesday's trade had been
marked by some profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
It was pretty quiet Tuesday with volumes low and not much
happening, Wright said.
</P>
<P>
"In the Asian markets there wasn't much direction. There was a
little bit of profit-taking and a bit of weakness in resources
with the overnight drop in metal prices."
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed down 11.3 points at 2639.4.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 266.95 million shares valued at 544.3
million U.S. dollars, with falls outnumbering rises by 619 to 463.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index slid by 11.6 points to 4551.9 while
the All Resources Index was 12.2 points weaker at 1109.7.
</P>
<P>
Among major resource companies, BHP company shed 25 cents to 14
Australian dollars and global miner Rio Tinto fell 31.8 cents to
18.2 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Base metals miner MIM was the most heavily traded stock with
16.377 million shares exchanged at a value of 9.2 million U.S.
dollars and its shares shedding 1 cent to 84 Australian cents.
</P>
<P>
The banking index declined 12.6 points to reach 5648.3 with
National Australia Bank dropping 23.2 cents to 21.64 Australian
dollars and the Commonwealth Bank of Australia losing 22 cents to
18.48 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ANZ Banking Group, which has its annual general meeting
Wednesday, fell 4 cents to 10.12 Australian dollars and Westpac
Banking Corp. gained 14.6 cents to 10.44 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 19.3 points to 1018.3 while spot gold
bullion in Sydney was trading at 286.8 U.S. dollars, down 90 cents
on Monday's close of 287.85 dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
