<HEADLINE> Foreign Car Manufacturers to Expand Business in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Car manufacturers from
France, Italy, Sweden and Korea are expected to expand business
in South Africa in the near future, local daily Sowetan reported
today.
</P>
<P>
French motor giant Renault is to relocate its entire export
operations center for the East Africa and Indian Ocean regions to
South Africa from March 1.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Italian car manufacturer Fiat and Swedish car maker
Volvo will also make similar announcement soon, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Despite bleak predictions for the motor industry this year,
local motor industrialists said, Volvo, Fiat and Renault will
feature more prominantly in South Africa, while Korean
manufacturers Hyundai, Daewoo and Sanyong are also looking at
expansion.
</P>
<P>
The move by Renault is regarded as a significant step for the
car maker, one of the ten top manufacturers in the world, and
will include all export, distribution of vehicles and after sales
aspects.
</P>
<P>
"This move reflects not only the importance with which Renault
France views South Africa as a hub for business activities within
the region, but also the increasing prominence of the country as
an export market for the company's products," said Richard
Nyhout, Renault's current regional director.
</P>
<P>
Renault has had a fairly successful run in the local motoring
industry since re-entering South Africa more than two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Manny de Canha, managing director of Renault's South African
partner Imperial Car Imports, predicted recently that the number
of Renault dealerships would be doubled from 10 to 20 over the
next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
