<HEADLINE> Kenya's Paper Firm Replants Trees to Protect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Pan African Papermill
is scheduled to replant trees this year on about 3,000 hectares
of land in west Kenya to protect environment, according to a
Daily Nation report today.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper quoted the firm's forest manager, Philip
Diro, as saying that the trees would be replanted where the
company had harvested as well as in open areas.
</P>
<P>
Although the company harvests about 1,000 hectares of trees
each year, he noted, it always replants on a larger area.
</P>
<P>
The firm has replanted trees on some 26,500 hectares since
1987 against 14,000 hectares harvested since the company started
its operations in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The Webuye-based company manufactures pulp and paper for both
the local and export markets. 
</P>
