<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Stock Market Capitalization Drops in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' stock market
capitalization in 1997 fell by 41 percent to 1.251 trillion pesos
(30.5 billion U.S. dollars) from a year ago, due to the financial
storm sweeping Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency Tuesday quoted a year-end report
made by the Philippine Stock Exchange as saying the fall of the
market capitalization was mainly caused by less initial public
offerings (IPOs) and flights of funds.
</P>
<P>
The report said the IPOs only accounted for 1.7 percent of the
total capitalization last year.
</P>
<P>
Most corporations decided to suspend their IPOs until the
financial meltdown has stabilized while those going to the public
experienced a lull in their share performance, it added.
</P>
<P>
Due to less IPOs, the report said, the capital raised from the
new corporations decreased by 63 percent to about 10.074 billion
pesos (245.7 million dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Despite this scenario, there is a strong indication that the
stock market kicked off on a positive note this year, with its
composite index reaching a record high in last week's rally, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the stock market would enjoy brisk trading buoyed
by the strong economic fundamentals the government has laid out to
cushion the impact of further economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund also predicted that the
Philippines had posted the highest growth rate in the region in
1997 and would first weather the financial storm before the end of
1999.
</P>
<P>
"Given the proper restraint and sound economic decisions, the
Philippines is set to survive the financial crisis in the region,"
the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
