<HEADLINE> Eritrea, Burundi to Enhance Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Eritrea and Burundi have
agreed to reinforce their economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest issue of English weekly, Eritrea
Profile, this was contained in a joint communique issued in
Asmara, capial of Eritrea at the end of a two-day official visit
to Eritrea by President Pierre Buyoya of Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The communique said, Eritrea President Isaias Afwerki and his
Burundian counterpart expressed their satisfaction at the general
agreement of cooperation signed in Bujunbura on December 8, 1997
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Burundian president and Isaias held talks on
Eritrean-Burundian ties as well as regional and international
issues, according to the communique.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Burundi, Isaias recalled that while the
government of Eritrea had welcomed the Arusha peace initiative as
an appropriate regional forum for facilitating a solution to the
situation, it had consistently rejected the imposition of
economic sanctions which was bound to be counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya said the overall security situation in Burundi has
improved significantly in spite of the difficulties resulting
from the economic sanctions, and expressed his firm belief that
the internal dialogue underway will impose itself as the driving
element in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya paid a visit to Eritrea last week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
