<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets US Defense Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
expressed his hope here today that the armies of China and the United
States will maintain a good momentum of development to ensure the
substantial and stable advancement of relations.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with visiting U.S. Secretary of Defense William
Cohen, Jiang said Cohen's visit will help enhance understanding
and trust between the two armies and the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"Through my October visit to the U.S., we have achieved the
goal of enhancing mutual understanding, broadening common
understanding, developing cooperation and jointly building the
future," said Jiang, commenting on his meeting with President
Bill Clinton last October.
</P>
<P>
"We have reached an important consensus on the development
orientation of the Sino-US ties geared to the 21st century," said
Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that exchanges between the two armied forces
have been "very active" over the past year, and noted that the
development trend remains "positive".
</P>
<P>
Jiang also expressed sincere gratitude for the US assistance
for quake-stricken areas in China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the United States attaches great importance to the
development of friendly cooperative ties with China, and noted
that good relations are in the best interests of the people in
both countries.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation and exchanges between the armies of the two
countries have witnessed a good beginning and this is an important
part of the bilateral ties, said Cohen.
</P>
<P>
Cohen noted that this is his eighth visit to China, and
expressed his sincere desire to visit China again in order to
further enhance understanding and cooperation between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Cohen conveyed US President Clinton's regards to Jiang, and
noted that the American leader looks forward to his forthcoming
visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Jiang asked Cohen to pass on his best regards to President
Clinton, and said he too looks forward to Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation left Beijing for Tokyo shortly after
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Cohen led a 57-member U.S. delegation on a three-day official
visit to China as guest of Vice-Chairman of the Central Military
Commission Chi Haotian, who also serves as a state councillor and
defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Cohen is the first US cabinet member to visit China since
President Jiang's visit the United States in October 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
