<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> mee012001hke - Khatami Reiterates No Need to Have Ties with US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 20 (Xinhua) - Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami has reiterated that there is no need for Iran to resume
ties with the United States since Washington still adopts
hegemonist policies.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA Tuesday, Khatami
made the remark Monday night while addressing a large group of
people at the mausoleum of the late spiritual leader Ayatollah
Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
"Today we do not need to have the United States at our side, we
can go ahead without the help of the United States," he said,
accusing Washington of "behaving like lords of the world and
imposing sanctions on every country."
</P>
<P>
In his first televised speech to the American people as
president on January 8, Khatami said "Iran feels no need to have
diplomatic ties with the U.S." since Washington did not change its
policies towards Iran.
</P>
<P>
However, he called for cultural dialogue between the Iranian
and American nations. His call was interpreted as a goodwill
signal that, if handled well, could lead to a thaw in bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Washington welcomed Khatami's signal but call for direct
government-to-government dialogue. And it set as conditions that
Tehran stop "sponsoring international terrorism, seeking weapons
of mass destruction and sabotaging the Middle East peace process."
</P>
<P>
Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, nevertheless, on
Friday ruled out ties between the two governments, saying any
relationship with the U.S. would be harmful to the Iranian nation
and the Islamic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei stressed that the Iranian nation would never give up
its values and beliefs under pressure from outside.
</P>
<P>
Echoing Khamenei's stance, Khatami also said "We have decided
not to succumb to oppressive pressure and as long as there are
people who apply coercive pressure on others and resort to force,
and as long as there are world powers which seek to base their
relations with other nations on the principle of oppressive
pressure on those nations, they cannot expect anything from the
Iranian nation."
</P>
<P>
He said the fruit of the Islamic Revolution has been Iran's
liberation from the yoke of the U.S. The Iranian people "attained
their lost dignity after paying a very high cost for it and they
would never give it away at any price," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran aims at eliminating tension in the world and
forging relations with world nations on the basis of mutual
respect.
</P>
<P>
He further diagnosed the "main reason for Washington's improper
policies as the existence of the Zionist regime (Israel) in the
region" and termed Israel as the main cause of tension in the
world.
</P>
<P>
It is a group of terrorists that want to oppress world nations
and impose their own selfish will, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Urges to Set Rules for Trans-national </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Leonardo Simao, Minister of
Foreign Affairs and Cooperation of Mozambique said that his
government has advocated to set regulations for the use of the
trans-national rivers in the region.
</P>
<P>
Simao made the statement at a press conference held here
Monday, according to local newspaper, Noticias today.
</P>
<P>
Water would be an important issue in the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) meeting to be held in Maputo on 29
and 30 of the month, he said.
</P>
<P>
The use of river water is especially important for Mozambique,
a country which shares most of its rivers with its neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
Simao said that his country wants to share the river water
with its neighbors on agreed regulations.
</P>
<P>
SADC has already had an agreement, but it is not signed yet.
</P>
<P>
Simao said that Mozambican Government also hopes the
agreements on communications, transport and weather forecasting
will be approved in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
About 400 people from SADC countries are to attend the
meeting, the first ever held in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
SADC has 14 members. They are South Africa, Angola, Botswana,
Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Mauritius, Namibia, Congo (K),
Seychelles, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
