<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Foreign Exchange Flows into Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Foreign exchange inflow into
Zambia in 1997 was 268.782 million U.S. Dollars, 1.084 million
dollars more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Out of the amount, 140.207 million dollars came from donors,
according to Financial Mail.
</P>
<P>
Debt servicing continued to consume most of the foreign
exchange as out of the total inflow 146.013 million went to
service debt, according to the weekly newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Receipts from Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) amounted
to 45.05 million dollars while the rest came from other
non-government sources such as non-traditional exports.
</P>
<P>
The increase in purchase from ZCCM came as a result of
shortage of foreign exchange between September and December
compounded by the need to import maize from abroad to meet the
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from Bank of Zambia, the need for more
exchange also forced the central bank to offload foreign exchange
onto the exchange market with a hope of stabilizing the Kwacha
(Zambian currency).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
