<HEADLINE> Aborted Coup Hurts Zambia's Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's tourism has suffered
from the October 28 aborted coup especially immediately after the
coup attempt, according to Financial Mail.
</P>
<P>
The local weekly newspaper today quoted Gaudenzio Rossi,
President of Hotels and Catering Association of Zambia (HCAZ), as
saying that his country has suffered from bad publicity in the
last few months following the foiled coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
"I am really depressed, the room occupancy in most hotels has
drastically gone down. Some hotels are completely empty. I do not
think I have seen a situation like this in the last 20 years," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the fact that some donors seem to be biased
against the Zambian government is also affecting tourism
industry.
</P>
<P>
"The industry now faces great liquidity problems as a result
of these bad months. We cannot even borrow from financial
institutions because most hotels have already overborrowed," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are even facing problems of pay taxes and salaries for our
workers," he said.
</P>
<P>
From about December 1996 and throughout 1997, there was a booming
business in the hotel industry until the last three months, he said.
</P>
<P>
The tourism official urged all politicians to resolve their
differences as soon as possible so that the industry as well as
others can survive.
</P>
<P>
He said that as an industry, it lacks a good public relations
which could go in other countries to counteract these bad
publicity.
</P>
<P>
Rossi called on the government to put in place a strong public
relations company to do this job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
