<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Undertakes Projects for Tribal Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
undertake a 2.34 billion-taka (about 51.71 million U.S. dollars)
package of development projects in the Chittagong Hill Tracts
(CHT), the national new agency BSS reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The projects will be implemented by the CHT Development Board
(CHTDB) from March this year in the three districts of Rangamati,
Khagrachhari and Bandarban, following the restoration of peace
there after the signing of the CHT agreement between the
government and the tribals there early last month.
</P>
<P>
The package is divided into 30 sub-projects including
rehabilitation of 21,000 families affected by insurgency in the
past two decades; construction of 132 kilometers of road, 90 free
primary schools and 34 secondary schools; renovation of 150
existing educational institutions; and raising of horticulture
gardens on private land.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1976, the CHTDB has been carrying out
multidimensional development activities to uplift the
socioeconomic conditions of the people in the Chittagong Hill
Tracts region, Southeast Bangladesh.  
</P>
</TEXT>
