<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leprosy Gets Less Threatening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The chronic infectious
disease of leprosy has become less threatening in the world, the
chairman of the International Federation of Dermatology, Dr
Terence Ryan has said.
</P>
<P>
Leprosy cases globally have dropped to less than a million at
present from two million 35 years ago, Ryan told the Third
International Continuing Medical Education Conference in Moshi in
north Tanzania, Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Although the prevalence of the disease in Brazil, India,
Myanmar, Nigeria and Indonesia remains to be a public health
hazard, he said, it is not as perilous as in other countries
where patients need not to be isolated, he told some 100 medical
experts from the United States, European and African countries
attending the conference last week.
</P>
<P>
Leprosy, caused by microbacterium, lepra, chiefly affects skin
and peripheral nerves.
</P>
<P>
Ryan, from Britain, said untreated cases of leprosy have
resulted in deformities and disabilities such as severe visual
impairment.
</P>
<P>
"Our problem is when the disease becomes rare many people tend
to forget about it," he said, adding that the only way is to look
at the skin to detect symptoms.
</P>
<P>
Ryan said IFD is supported by 130 national dermatological
societies representing 30,000 dermatologists worldwide. The
organizations provide ideas, facilities and funds to support IFD
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Open Sees Off Muster, Ivanisevic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Eighth seeded Thomas Muster
and thirteenth seeded Goran Ivanisevic ended their title chasing
from start as both were eliminated by their first-round opponents
on Tuesday, biggest surprise so far in the Australian Open in
Melbourne, Australia.
</P>
<P>
Muster, world number 10, was huliminated by Swedish journeyman
Jan Apell in straight sets, 6-4, 7-6 (7-5), 7-5, while
Ivanisevic, 15th in the world, fell to Dutch Jan Siemerink after
four sets,  6-2, 7-6 (7-3), 3-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Muster, winner of the 1995 French Open, piled up little answer
to Apell, who is 233 ranking places below him, when the Swede
stole the spotlight from the former world number one player.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian saved two match points in the 10th game, but could
not hold on, and Apell celebrated his victory by punching the air
in delight after he sent Muster packed.
</P>
<P>
It was the worst performance for the Austrian in his ten-year
appearance in the first Grand Slam of the year.
</P>
<P>
And Ivanisevic, who also was beaten in the first round here in
1990, never recovered from a dubious line call on a break point at
4-4 which was judged favour to the Dutch, surrendering his match
after he fought out six more deuce points after appeal.
</P>
<P>
Apell next meets the winner of the first-round match between
compatriot Thomas Nydahl and Frenchman Lionel Roux, while
Siemerink is likely to face Britain's Tim Henman.
</P>
<P>
World number one Martina Hingis survived in Tuesday's match in
the Melbourne Park by beating German Wiltrud Probst 6-1, 6-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
