<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Can Get Larger Jute Market Share: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Jute industrial experts have
urged the Bangladeshi government to take measures to expand the
country's share in the international jute market, according to a
local press report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's jute industry enjoys an ample scope for expansion
and could compete with other jute product manufacturing countries,
Shams-ul-Haque, an adviser of the Bangladesh Supreme Jute and
Knitex Ltd. (SJKL), was quoted as saying at a meeting on jute
industrial management recently.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh exported 790,000 tons of jute products in the
1996-97 fiscal year, accounting for 54 percent of the world market
demand and earning 6.4 billion taka (about 142 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Competing for the remaining 46 percent of the market would not
be hard work if jute products could be made price-competitive in
the global market, Shams-ul-Haque said.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that jute is facing challenges from
artificial fibers and synthetics. "But artificial fibers and
synthetics are hazardous for the environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Manzoor-ul Karim, chairman of the Board of Directors of the
SJKL, said annual global demand for jute yarn stands at 250,000
tons, of which Bangladesh meets 47 percent, but "we could easily
go for meeting 65 percent of the world demand."
</P>
<P>
The jute industry, the backbone of Bangladesh's national
economy, has been neglected for years, he stated, urging the
government and jute industrialists to find ways to develop it.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh government is going to submit a report to the
World Bank (WB) soon at the latter's request for the WB-aided
Revised Jute Sector Reform Program to help boost the country's
jute sector, the press report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
