<HEADLINE> Cohen Says His China Trip Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense
William Cohen said today that his visit to China has had a
positive impact on promoting bilateral and military
relations between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the end of his three-day
official visit, Cohen said that relations between the two countries
have greatly improved since Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit
to the U.S. in October last year.
</P>
<P>
He expressed appreciation for China's "very constructive" moves
to promote the relations between the two armies and two countries.
</P>
<P>
He noted that military cooperation between the two
countries is proceeding smoothly in many areas, including exchanges of
visit by senior officials, reciprocal naval visits and
cooperation in humanitarian operations.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that the defense departments of the two
countries will continue to expand cooperation. He said the
two sides will adopt a modest, step-by-step approach to
establish mechanisms to increase confidence and reducing
misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said his visit will have a positive effect on the
progress of multilevel and multichannel cooperation between the
two sides, and will help create a sound atmosphere for President
Bill Clinton's visit to China later this year.  
</P>
