<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Foreign Reserve Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's foreign exchange
reserve rose by 4.4 percent to 1.67 billion U.S. dollars on
January 8 from 1.6 billion dollars about a month earlier, the
local press reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The reserve, which dropped to a record low of 1.58 billion
dollars at the end of November, showed a rising trend which
officials of Bangladesh Bank, the country's central bank, said was
the result of a satisfactory increase in export.
</P>
<P>
The country registered a 20-percent growth in export in the
first five months of the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings rose to 2.11 billion dollars in the
July-November period, as against the 1.76 billion dollars in the
corresponding period of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials, however, termed the present position of foreign
exchange reserve as "not safe" although the position has
"stabilized to a great extent."
</P>
<P>
Normally, a country's foreign exchange reserve is considered
"safe" if it is enough for paying three and half months' import
bills. But Bangladesh's present foreign exchange reserve could
meet import bills only for a maximum of three months, a high
official at the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
the country's inadequate foreign exchange reserve position
might be further affected by the recent economic crisis in
Southeast Asian countries and South Korea, the official said,
referring to the money sent home by Bangladeshi workers in those
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
