<HEADLINE> Lithuania: Charter With U.S. Not Directed at Third Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 19 (Xinhua) -- A pact signed Friday between the
three Baltic states and the United States is not directed at other
countries, said Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas Monday.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return from Washington to the Lithuanian capital of
Vilnius, Brazauskas said the Charter of Partnership is not a bad
thing for Russia and should not lead to its negative responses.
</P>
<P>
He told the Interfax news agency at the airport that his
country and Russia might one day sign a similar document.
</P>
<P>
There should be continued preparation to create favorable
conditions for cooperation and confidence-building between Vilnius
and Moscow, so as to forge documents governing bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Last October, Russian President Boris Yeltsin offered, in what
Brazauskas described as "a positive move," to forge relations of
good-neighborliness and mutual trust with the Baltic states.
</P>
<P>
Brazauskas said many people paid attention only to Russia's
offer of security cover for the Baltic states, but did not notice
its call for cooperation on economic and ecological issues.
</P>
<P>
The Lithuanian president said the U.S.-Baltic Charter of
Partnership signed in Washington is an important step for his
country to approach the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
He predicted that Lithuania could join the NATO in five years.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.S.-Baltic Charter of Partnership, the United States
promised to help Lithuania, Estonia and Lativa acquire full NATO
memberships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
