<HEADLINE> Foreign Buyers lead Thai Bourse Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors' renewed
buying helped push up the Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index
by 9.8 percent on Monday, the local press quoted analysts as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The surge indicated foreigners' renewed confidence in the
country's financial reform program, they said.
</P>
<P>
The SET index rose 37.71 points in heavy volume to close at
420.72, the first time since early December the Thai bourse traded
over the 420-point mark, as foreign and local buyers snapped up
banking and technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
The rally came after International Monetary Fund (IMF) chief
Michel Camdessus on Friday praised the Thai government's efforts
to stick to the terms set in the 17.2 billion US dollar bailout
program.
</P>
<P>
The market was anticipating positive news from Washington,
where visiting Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda began a
series of talks with IMF and American officials for more funding
and easier terms.
</P>
<P>
Hopes are high that Tarrin will win relaxation of the strict
austerity measures attached to the IMF rescue package, in
particular the condition that Thailand showed a budget surplus
equal to one percent of gross domestic product (GDP) in the fiscal
1998, which ends in the coming September.
</P>
<P>
On the currency market, the baht closed lightly stronger at
52.90-53.00 from Friday's close of 52.95-53.30.  
</P>
</TEXT>
