<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia' Stock Prices Surge, Rupiah Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah descended
sharply to 9,550 against the U.S. dollar Monday on a combination
of political tensions and mounting concerns over the private
sector debt, "the Jakarta Post" daily Tuesday quoted currency
dealers as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the weakening rupiah did not riddle the stock market
as stock prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange rose 6.06 percent
after five local private banks announced a merger, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The merged banks will constitute the country's largest listed
private bank with total assets of 50 trillion rupiah (5.55 billion
U.S. dollars) and total equity of 5 trillion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
"It's just a bit strange to see the movement of the rupiah
Monday. It stabilized in the morning session before plunged to
almost 10,000 after lunch break," a local private bank chief
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The spot rupiah closed at 9,550/9,750 to the dollar against an
opening of 8,600/8,800 in the morning before nose-diving to 9,900
after lunch break.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah fell to a record low of 11,000 per dollar on January
8, but it strengthened to between 7,800 and 8,500 after Indonesia
and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) signed a reform package
on January 15.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has lost more than 200 percent of its value against
the dollar since July last year.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said reports on rioting in several small towns in East
Java and a protest at the House of Representatives compound put
more pressure on the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said angry mobs attacked on shops and rice mills
in the area of Banyuwangi, East Java last Saturday. On Monday,
about 200 people held a protest at the House of Representatives
building, demanding that President Soeharto step down and calling
on the government to reduce the soaring prices of staples.
</P>
<P>
"Adding to the political tension, the rupiah's fall is largely
attributed to foreign investors' concern about the private sector
debt in Indonesia," a chief dealer said.
</P>
<P>
"It's just a pity the government has not mentioned any solution
to this problem (private sector debt) in the economic reforms
announced by the government last week," the dealer said.
</P>
<P>
According to the pact signed here last Thursday by Indonesia
and the IMF, Indonesia will conduct a wide-ranging economic and
financial reform, including reviewing the 1998-99 state budget
draft, curtailing the government financial support for the
national car project and scrapping some agriculture monopolies.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government said the country's overall external
debt was 140 billion dollars at the end of last year. It did not
mention the private sector portion, but an earlier figure showed
private sector debt accounted for about 55 percent of the total
debt.
</P>
<P>
About 9.6 billion dollars of the total amount will mature by
March this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inter-ASEAN Exports Grow at 28.3 Percent Per Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Exports among ASEAN countries
have grown from 43.26 billion US dollars in 1993 to almost 80
billion in 1996, an average yearly growth of 28.3 percent, ASEAN
Secretary General Rodolfo C. Severino said.
</P>
<P>
In the process, inter-ASEAN exports rose from almost 21 percent
to 24.7 percent, as a share of total ASEAN exports, Severino said
at a briefing for the mission of the U.S.-ASEAN Business Council
here Monday, officials at the ASEAN secretariat disclosed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Severino said the figures show the results of the
implementation of the Common Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT)
scheme.
</P>
<P>
"We are now only five years away from the completion of the
ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA). 42,252 tariff lines - more than 90
percent of all ASEAN tariff lines - have already been included in
the CEPT scheme leading to AFTA. Since 1993, when CEPT started,
average tariffs on the products involved have fallen by half, from
12.76 to 6.38 percent today," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary General emphasized that with the admission of
Laos and Myanmar, the ASEAN market is now as large as China's, and
according to the World Trade Organization (WTO), ASEAN is now the
fourth in exports, behind the European Union, the United States
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
