<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will launch a 300
million Rupees (about 5 million U.S. dollars) program to improve
the cultivation and use of indigenous medicinal plants this year,
the Daily News newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The five-year program aims at conserving and promoting the use
of medicinal plants in the country on a sustainable basis. The
World Bank has decided to grant a fund of 4.5 million dollars for
the program, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The government has recognized the vital role played by the
indigenous medicine sector to health services, especially in the
rural areas. It thus has stipulated policies to encourage the
development and expansion of the sector, the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
