<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Slashes Budget for State-run Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Chile will slash its budget
for state-run enterprises by 17.8 percent this year as it braces
for the financial impact of the economic turbulence in Southeast
Asia, a senior Chilean official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean government will cut its budget for state-run
enterprise from 1.91 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 to 1.58 billion
dollars this year, Finance Minister Eduardo Aninat said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will cut its budget for copper mining by
100 million dollars and for the oil industry by 127 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the minister voiced confidence in the Chilean economy,
saying it will withstand the impact of the Southeast Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will not alter its plan for a 6.5 to 7.0
percent economic growth this year while keeping the inflation rate
under 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said Chile has 25 billion U.S. dollars of foreign debt, but
its gross domestic product hit 79 billion U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
