<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Blast Injures 2 in Indonesia's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- A small bomb exploded at a
low-cost apartment building in Tanah Tinggi, Central Jakarta,
Sunday evening, injuring at least two people, security authorities
and news reports here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Police said the explosion, which also damaged the apartment
building, was carried out by supporters of the outlawed People's
Democratic Party (PRD).
</P>
<P>
Police arrested several leaders of the PRD for allegedly
masterminding riots on July 27, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Central Jakarta police precinct Iman Haryatna said one
of the apartment building occupants has been caught and detained
while search is under way for two others on suspicion that they
played a key role in the bomb explosion.
</P>
<P>
Haryatna said the bomb, which was apparently intended to
trigger social unrest, exploded unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
From the apartment, police seized nine detonators, one timer,
eight jars containing gun powder, two cellular phones, three
beepers, a laptop computer, batteries, wires, a number of
documents including books on international terrorism and private
letters, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The intended target of the bomb has not yet been confirmed by
police, said Haryatna.
</P>
<P>
"We are investigating this," he said, adding that it was
possible the activities were aimed at sparking unrest and violence
ahead of the plenary session of the People's Consultative Assembly
(MPR).
</P>
<P>
The MPR convenes in March to elect the next president and vice
president.  
</P>
</TEXT>
