<HEADLINE> Argentina, Canada to Further Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem and visiting Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien signed a
number of accords here on Monday to further their cooperation in
education, social security, anti-land mines and other fields.
</P>
<P>
The education agreement calls for the increased exchange of
information, the training of students and teachers, and the
transfer of technology for the development of information systems
in schools.
</P>
<P>
The social security accord will ensure that retired Canadians
who move to Argentina continue to receive pension benefits from
Canada and not rely on Argentina's welfare system.
</P>
<P>
In a declaration of intent, Menem and Chretien vowed to work
toward the goal of turning the South American continent into "the
first region in the world free of anti-personnel mines."
</P>
<P>
They said Canada and Argentina would work together to help
other countries unearth land mines and treat people injured by the
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Chretien also promised that Canadian investment in Argentina
would increase.
</P>
<P>
Chretien arrived in Argentina Saturday on the third leg of a
four-nation Latin America tour that has taken him to Mexico and
Brazil. He will leave for Chile on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
