<HEADLINE> Italian FM Says Somalia Aid Depends on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini Monday warned Somalia's leaders that international aid to
rebuild the country will come only after the process of national
reconciliation has begun.
</P>
<P>
His comments came one month ahead of scheduled talks between
the country's two main warlords to finalize the terms of a peace
accord they agreed upon in Cairo last month.
</P>
<P>
Dini said at the meeting of ministers of member states and
partners of the Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD)
that Somali leaders should set aside "the illusion that they can
solve their differences by force."
</P>
<P>
He urged them to seek an urgent negotiated settlement. "Without
that, there can be no funds to reconstruct their country," Dini
said.
</P>
<P>
Six of the IGAD member states -- Djibouti, Ethiopia, Eritrea,
Kenya, Sudan and Uganda -- together with representatives from
donor countries Britain, Canada, France, Italy, Norway,
Switzerland, the United States, and the European Union, as well as
U.N. delegates, attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was co-chaired by Dini and Kenyan Foreign Minister
Bonaya Godana.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has been torn by factional warfare since the oust of
the late dictator Mohamed Siad Barre in 1991.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 30,000 people have died in clan fighting that has
continued despite several peace accords. 
</P>
</TEXT>
