<HEADLINE> Mexico Warns Against Foreign Involvement in Local Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Mexican Foreign Secretary
Rosario Green on Monday warned some foreign groups against their
alleged involvement in the four-year conflict in Chiapas state.
</P>
<P>
Foreign aid, humanitarian and rights groups, Green said, are
welcome as long as they limit themselves to the role of observers
in the restive state where Zapatista rebels rose up in 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, she said, they would be prosecuted upon exceeding
their role as observers, because Mexican law forbids foreigners to
become involved in the country's domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, immigration authorities expelled 11 foreign-born
priests from Chiapas, mostly on charges of violating the terms of
their visas by engaging in political activities.
</P>
<P>
Last November, a French journalist was ordered out for visiting
a Chiapas village controlled by Zapatista rebels.
</P>
<P>
Green said she would meet her European Union counterparts next
month to explain the Mexican government's response to the December
22 massacre of 45 people in the Chiapas hamlet of Acteal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
