<DOCNO> XIE19980120.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Rupee Depreciates by 8.7 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan currency, the
rupee, depreciated by 8.7 percent in 1997 and the value of the
currency is expected to decline at a faster pace this year, local
economic analysts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Following the sharp currency depreciations in Southeast Asia
last year, there had been pressure for a devaluation of the Sri
Lankan rupee, they said.
</P>
<P>
After remaining relatively stable in the third quarter of 1997
at 58 per U.S. dollar, the rupee dropped to 61.6 per dollar by the
end of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
The analysts said the government would not devalue the currency
this year, given the central bank's stance on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The bank has opposed a steep devaluation of the currency,
fearing it would have an adverse impact on inflation, interest
rates and fiscal deficit.
</P>
<P>
The analysts said the bank will maintain its stance until it
assesses the impact of the financial crisis in Southeast Asia on
the Sri Lankan economy and the degree of stability that would
re-emerge in the Asian currency market.
</P>
<P>
However, they pointed out that a continuing current account
deficit and weaker capital inflows, due to the Southeast Asian
economic turmoil, would put pressure on the rupee.
</P>
<P>
The central bank, while trying to avoid a devaluation, is
likely to let the rupee undergo an accelerated depreciation in
1998, the analysts said, predicting a 10- to 12-percent slide for
this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
