<HEADLINE> Beckenbauer Insists Single European Candidate for World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Franz Beckenbauer said the victim
of the joint bid from England and Germany for the 2006 World Cup
would be European's lose to host the world soccer premier
meetings.
</P>
<P>
"If England and Germany keep acting like they have been and
arguing for the right to host the World Cup, it will simply favour
a third candidate, namely Africa," said the German bid ambassador
in an interview with German sports agency SID on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Europe will only stand a chance if it unites behind one
single candidate," the Bayern Munich president added.
</P>
<P>
Beckenbauer, who was reelected as Bayern president for another
three years last November, firmly denied to co-host the World Cup,
saying it would be too expensive and would inevitably lead to a
clash between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Beckenbauer, whose club was current second in the Bundesliga
with four points trailing to Kaiserslautern, urged UEFA president
Lennart Johansson to make a decision as soon as possible to have
only one bidding country.
</P>
<P>
"UEFA must exercise its authority as soon as possible," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In the interview, Beckembauer also said he tried to transform
Bayern into a shareholding company. 
</P>
