<HEADLINE> Thai Airline to Seek Delay of New Aircraft Delivery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 20 (Xinhua) -- Thai Airways International
(THAI) has decided to open talks with Boeing and Airbus aircraft
producers for postponing the delivery of 17 new planes by at least
three years.
</P>
<P>
Of the 17 planes ordered, 11 are scheduled for delivery this
year while the remainder are due in 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
The proposed delivery delay is aimed at reducing THAI's
expenditure and minimizing the impact on the Thai currency baht
and stock market, the newspaper The Nation reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In fiscal 1997, THAI's net profit was down by 600 million baht
from 1996, but sales costs surged by 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Most of the airline's revenue is derived from its international
operation while its domestic flights operate at a loss.
</P>
<P>
Because of a sharp decline in the number of travelers in Asia,
THAI will cut its flights to Seoul and Ho Chi Minh City and other
unprofitable routes to Indonesia and the Philippines may also come
under the ax.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Transport and Communications Ministry has
requested THAI to cut its 1998 budget by 6 billion baht (112
million U.S. dollars) through canceling some loss-making
international routes and suspending overtime pay for its
engineers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
