<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Indian Tripe Suffers Suicides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Three Indians of the
Guarani-Kaiowa tripe in western Brazil committed suicide in the
last two weeks, an Indian rights group said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nereu Schneider, of the Indian Missionary Council, said that 27
members of the village in Bororo, Mato Grosso do Sul, committed
suicide in 1997, bringing the total of suicides to 158 in the past
11 years.
</P>
<P>
Schneider blamed the suicides on poverty, alcoholism, and the
loss of ancestral lands.
</P>
<P>
The Guarani-Kaiowa tripe have lost more than half of their land
to ranchers as settlers flow into the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
There are about 250,000 Indians in Brazil, down from an
estimated 5 million when European explorers arrived in 1500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
