<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Slashes at Wage Arrears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
criticized Monday of the cabinet's persistent state sector wage
arrears, Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, in meeting top cabinet officials on his first work day
in the New Year, said a major contributor to the late salary
payment is an incomplete account transfer system.
</P>
<P>
A number of problems, including the wage arrears, are the left
over from 1997, he told Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and
deputy prime ministers Boris Nemtsov and Anatoly Chubais.
</P>
<P>
While some federal organs were to be blamed for failing to
allocate state funds immediately to local authorities, the cabinet
should still be held responsible for the wage problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, in Kremlin, reviewed the practice of economic and
social policies in 1997, and discussed the cabinet's work schedule
and each top government officials' responsibilities in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Yeltsin discussed separately with Interior
Minister Anatoly Kulikov and Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev about
the situation in Chechnya and a pay rise for military servicemen.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin returned to Kremlin on Saturday after nearly two weeks
at Valday, a resort residence 300 kilometers northwest of Moscow,
to fully recover from a viral chest infection last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
