<HEADLINE> Makinen Leads After Monte Carlo First Leg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 19 (Xinhua) -- World champion Tommi Makinen led
the first leg of the Monte Carlo rally on Monday after won four of
the six stages of the day in Monte Carlo, Monaco.
</P>
<P>
The Finn, staying in an unprecedented hunt for third world
title en route, lodged at the top of the standings, one minute
08.5 seconds ahead of last year's Monte Carlo winner Piero Liatti
of Italy.
</P>
<P>
Makinen, in a Mitsubishi Lancer in which he won the
championship by the narrowest of margins from 1995 world champion
Scot Colin McRae last season, rounded off the day's race by a
amazing 44.8 seconds from Liatti, in a Subaru Impreza, in the
final stage.
</P>
<P>
Twice Monte Carlo winner Sainz, in a Toyota Corolla, was third,
another 09.6 seconds from the day's winner, on the 471.4-kilometer
leg from Monaco to Gap in the southern French Alps on the icy and
dirty road.
</P>
<P>
Didier Auriol of France, triple winner of the Monte Carlo rally
since 1990, crashed out of the top 30 after got a 30 seconds
penalty for a late arrival at the start of the third stage, and
damaged his front axle on the sixth laterly.
</P>
<P>
Spaniard Oriol Gomez and Uruguayan Gustavo Trelles abandoned
the race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
