<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Nordic Support to Baltic States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, January 19 (Xinhua) -- The governments of the five
Nordic countries -- Denmark, Finland, Iceland, Norway and Sweden
-- presented Monday to the European Commission a report on a
survey of Nordic support to the Baltic States in the area of
justice and home affairs.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that extensive work has already been
initiated in the Baltic states -- Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania --
in the area of justice and home affairs, such as the fight against
narcotics and organized crime, the strengthening of the judiciary
and prosecution system, the exchange of information about the
administration of asylum and refugee matters and the enhanced
external border control.
</P>
<P>
The Baltic states are undergoing a dynamic development in these
areas and that there is strong political will and ambition to take
the necessary measures, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report is a result of the agreement reached by the Nordic
and Baltic foreign ministers on a Swedish initiative at a
ministerial meeting in Bergen, Norway, on September 3-4, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was taken in the light of the statement by the
European Commission concerning the preparation of candidate
countries for membership negotiations and gradual admission to the
EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
