<HEADLINE> Manila Pushes for ASEAN Currency-to-Currency Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
pushing for the immediate adoption of the proposed
currency-to-currency trade payment scheme among the members of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
Local press quoted Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista
on Tuesday as saying that Manila wants to immediately implement
the scheme with Indonesia, Malaysia and Thailand, three ASEAN
members who were currently trapped in the financial storm.
</P>
<P>
The plan requires countries to settle trade flows among
themselves in their own currencies through an offset mechanism
instead of using the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The scheme would lower the countries' demand for the greenback
by at least 30 percent and conserve foreign exchange reserves,
thus helping stabilize the exchange rate between dollar and their
respective currencies.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said the scheme, conceptualized during the Manila
meeting of ASEAN finance ministers in November last year, is being
reviewed by the central banks of the corresponding ASEAN members.
</P>
<P>
He added that the scheme was not against the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
"It is a sensible scheme, it is not against the IMF, and no new
legislation is required," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Viet Nam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
