<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 91-day Treasury Bill Rate Drops in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 20 (Xinhua) -- The interest rate of the 91-day
Treasury bill, a benchmark used by banks to price their loans,
Monday dropped for the first time in eight weeks as the peso
continued gaining strength, local newspaper Business World
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the yield of the 91-day Treasury bill
plunged 1.537 percentage points to 18.587 percent from a six-year
high of 20.134 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
The fall of the rate of the 91-day Treasury bill would help
lower commercial banks' interest rates which were raised to
unreasonable levels as a result of the depreciation of the peso
since July last year.
</P>
<P>
It would also be beneficial to the manufacturing sector. In the
long run, it would help the country rebuild its economy which was
slowing down due to the financial meltdown.
</P>
<P>
"Basically, the drop in Treasury bill yields was because of the
appreciation of the peso, and an increase in the prices of the
stocks... obviously, money is back into the financial system and
banks are liquid again," the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The peso had strengthened for the ninth consecutive trading day
on Monday, appreciating to an average of 41 pesos against the U.S.
dollar from 41.352.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange traders said the peso continued to be boosted
by the dollar sales of banks and exporters. But analysts were not
yet convinced that the momentum will sustain for long since the
regional financial storm has not shown signs of termination.
</P>
<P>
Just two weeks ago, the peso fell to a historic low of 46.5
pesos per dollar, a fall of 76 percent from its pre-devaluation
average of 26.4 pesos a dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
